01585             break;

01588                 if ((offset <= 9))

01590             if (OCTEON_IS_MODEL(OCTEON_CN78XX_PASS1_X))
01591                 if ((offset <= 9))
01592                     return CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x0001180080800800ull) + ((offset) & 15) * 64;
01593 
01594             break;
01595         case OCTEON_CN66XX & OCTEON_FAMILY_MASK:
01596         case OCTEON_CNF71XX & OCTEON_FAMILY_MASK:
01597         case OCTEON_CN61XX & OCTEON_FAMILY_MASK:
01598         case OCTEON_CN63XX & OCTEON_FAMILY_MASK:
01599             if ((offset == 0))
01600                 return CVMX_ADD_IO_SEG(0x0001180080800400ull);
01601             break;
01602         case OCTEON_CN68XX & OCTEON_FAMILY_MASK:
01603             if ((offset <= 3))

01710 
01711 /**
01712  * cvmx_l2c_big_ctl
01713  *
01714  * L2C_BIG_CTL = L2C Big memory control register
01715  *
01716  *
01717  * Notes:
01718  * (1) BIGRD interrupts can occur during normal operation as the PP's are allowed to prefetch to
01719  *     non-existent memory locations.  Therefore, BIGRD is for informational purposes only.
01720  *
01721  * (2) When HOLEWR/BIGWR blocks a store L2C_VER_ID, L2C_VER_PP, L2C_VER_IOB, and L2C_VER_MSC will be
01722  *     loaded just like a store which is blocked by VRTWR.  Additionally, L2C_ERR_XMC will be loaded.
01723  */
01724 union cvmx_l2c_big_ctl {
01725     uint64_t u64;
01726     struct cvmx_l2c_big_ctl_s {
01727 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01728     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
01729     uint64_t maxdram                      : 4;  /**< Amount of configured DRAM.
01730                                                          0x0 = reserved.
01731                                                          0x1 = 512 MB.
01732                                                          0x2 = 1 GB.
01733                                                          0x3 = 2 GB.
01734                                                          0x4 = 4 GB.
01735                                                          0x5 = 8 GB.
01736                                                          0x6 = 16 GB.
01737                                                          0x7 = 32 GB.
01738                                                          0x8 = 64 GB.
01739                                                          0x9 = 128 GB.
01740                                                          0xA = 256 GB.
01741                                                          0xB = 512 GB.
01742                                                          0xC = 1 TB.
01743                                                          0xD-0xF= reserved.
01744                                                          Violations of this limit cause L2C to set L2C_TAD()_INT[BIGRD/BIGWR]. */

02423  *
02424  * L2C_BST_MEM = L2C MEM BIST Status
02425  *
02426  *
02427  * Notes:
02428  * (1) CLEAR_BIST must be written to 1 before START_BIST is written to 1 using a separate CSR write.
02429  *
02430  * (2) CLEAR_BIST must not be changed after writing START_BIST to 1 until the BIST operation completes
02431  *     (indicated by START_BIST returning to 0) or operation is undefined.
02432  */

02441     uint64_t rdffl                        : 1;  /**< BIST failure status for RDF */
02442     uint64_t vbffl                        : 4;  /**< BIST failure status for VBF0-3 */
02443 #else
02444     uint64_t vbffl                        : 4;
02445     uint64_t rdffl                        : 1;
02446     uint64_t reserved_5_61                : 57;

02448     uint64_t start_bist                   : 1;
02449 #endif
02450     } s;

02616 /**
02617  * cvmx_l2c_cbc#_holeerr
02618  *
02619  * This register records error information for HOLE* interrupts. The first HOLEWR error locks the
02620  * register until the logged error type is cleared; HOLERD never locks the register.
02621  */
02622 union cvmx_l2c_cbcx_holeerr {
02623     uint64_t u64;
02624     struct cvmx_l2c_cbcx_holeerr_s {
02625 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02626     uint64_t holerd                       : 1;  /**< Logged information is for a HOLERD error. */
02627     uint64_t holewr                       : 1;  /**< Logged information is for a HOLEWR error. */
02628     uint64_t reserved_59_61               : 3;
02629     uint64_t cmd                          : 8;  /**< Encoding of XMC command causing error. */
02630     uint64_t source                       : 7;  /**< XMC 'source' of request causing error. If SOURCE<6>==0, then SOURCE<5:0> is PPID, else
02631                                                          SOURCE<3:0> is BUSID of the IOB which made the request. */
02632     uint64_t node                         : 4;  /**< CCPI is not present. Should always read 0. */
02633     uint64_t addr                         : 40; /**< XMC address causing the error. This field is the physical address after hole removal and
02634                                                          index aliasing (if enabled). (The hole is between DR0 and DR1. Remove the hole by
02635                                                          subtracting 256MB from all L2/DRAM physical addresses >= 512 MB.) */
02636 #else
02637     uint64_t addr                         : 40;
02638     uint64_t node                         : 4;
02639     uint64_t source                       : 7;
02640     uint64_t cmd                          : 8;
02641     uint64_t reserved_59_61               : 3;
02642     uint64_t holewr                       : 1;
02643     uint64_t holerd                       : 1;
02644 #endif
02645     } s;
02646     struct cvmx_l2c_cbcx_holeerr_s        cn73xx;
02647     struct cvmx_l2c_cbcx_holeerr_s        cn78xx;

02649     struct cvmx_l2c_cbcx_holeerr_s        cnf75xx;

02848 /**
02849  * cvmx_l2c_cbc#_rsderr
02850  *
02851  * This register records error information for all CBC RSD errors.
02852  * An error locks the INDEX and [SYN] and sets the bit corresponding to the error received.
02853  * RSDDBE errors take priority and overwrite an earlier logged RSDSBE error. Only one of
02854  * [RSDSBE]/[RSDDBE] is set at any given time and serves to document which error the INDEX/[SYN]
02855  * is
02856  * associated with.
02857  * The syndrome is recorded for DBE errors, though the utility of the value is not clear.
02858  */
02859 union cvmx_l2c_cbcx_rsderr {
02860     uint64_t u64;
02861     struct cvmx_l2c_cbcx_rsderr_s {
02862 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02863     uint64_t rsddbe                       : 1;  /**< INDEX/SYN corresponds to a double-bit RSD ECC error */
02864     uint64_t rsdsbe                       : 1;  /**< INDEX/SYN corresponds to a single-bit RSD ECC error */
02865     uint64_t reserved_40_61               : 22;
02866     uint64_t syn                          : 8;  /**< Error syndrome. */
02867     uint64_t reserved_9_31                : 23;
02868     uint64_t tadnum                       : 3;  /**< Indicates the TAD FIFO containing the error. */
02869     uint64_t qwnum                        : 2;  /**< Indicates the QW containing the error. */
02870     uint64_t rsdnum                       : 4;  /**< Indicates the RSD that had the error. */
02871 #else
02872     uint64_t rsdnum                       : 4;
02873     uint64_t qwnum                        : 2;
02874     uint64_t tadnum                       : 3;
02875     uint64_t reserved_9_31                : 23;
02876     uint64_t syn                          : 8;
02877     uint64_t reserved_40_61               : 22;
02878     uint64_t rsdsbe                       : 1;
02879     uint64_t rsddbe                       : 1;
02880 #endif
02881     } s;
02882     struct cvmx_l2c_cbcx_rsderr_s         cn70xx;
02883     struct cvmx_l2c_cbcx_rsderr_s         cn70xxp1;
02884     struct cvmx_l2c_cbcx_rsderr_s         cn73xx;
02885     struct cvmx_l2c_cbcx_rsderr_s         cn78xx;
02886     struct cvmx_l2c_cbcx_rsderr_s         cn78xxp1;
02887     struct cvmx_l2c_cbcx_rsderr_s         cnf75xx;

02891 /**
02892  * cvmx_l2c_cfg
02893  *
02894  * Specify the RSL base addresses for the block
02895  *
02896  *                  L2C_CFG = L2C Configuration
02897  *
02898  * Description:
02899  */
02900 union cvmx_l2c_cfg {
02901     uint64_t u64;
02902     struct cvmx_l2c_cfg_s {
02903 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02904     uint64_t reserved_20_63               : 44;
02905     uint64_t bstrun                       : 1;  /**< L2 Data Store Bist Running
02906                                                          Indicates when the L2C HW Bist sequence(short or long) is
02907                                                          running. [L2C ECC Bist FSM is not in the RESET/DONE state] */
02908     uint64_t lbist                        : 1;  /**< L2C Data Store Long Bist Sequence
02909                                                          When the previous state was '0' and SW writes a '1',
02910                                                          the long bist sequence (enhanced 13N March) is performed.
02911                                                          SW can then read the L2C_CFG[BSTRUN] which will indicate
02912                                                          that the long bist sequence is running. When BSTRUN-=0,
02913                                                          the state of the L2D_BST[0-3] registers contain information
02914                                                          which reflects the status of the recent long bist sequence.
02915                                                          NOTE: SW must never write LBIST=0 while Long Bist is running
02916                                                          (ie: when BSTRUN=1 never write LBIST=0).
02917                                                          NOTE: LBIST is disabled if the MIO_FUS_DAT2.BIST_DIS
02918                                                          Fuse is blown. */
02919     uint64_t xor_bank                     : 1;  /**< L2C XOR Bank Bit
02920                                                          When both LMC's are enabled(DPRES1=1/DPRES0=1), this
02921                                                          bit determines how addresses are assigned to
02922                                                          LMC port(s).
02923                                                             XOR_BANK|  LMC#
02924                                                           ----------+---------------------------------
02925                                                               0     |   byte address[7]
02926                                                               1     |   byte address[7] XOR byte address[12]
02927                                                          Example: If both LMC ports are enabled (DPRES1=1/DPRES0=1)
02928                                                          and XOR_BANK=1, then addr[7] XOR addr[12] is used to determine
02929                                                          which LMC Port# a reference is directed to. */
02930     uint64_t dpres1                       : 1;  /**< DDR1 Present/LMC1 Enable
02931                                                          When DPRES1 is set, LMC#1 is enabled(DDR1 pins at
02932                                                          the BOTTOM of the chip are active).
02933                                                          NOTE: When both LMC ports are enabled(DPRES1=1/DPRES0=1),
02934                                                          see XOR_BANK bit to determine how a reference is
02935                                                          assigned to a DDR/LMC port. (Also, in dual-LMC configuration,
02936                                                          the address sent to the targeted LMC port is the
02937                                                          address shifted right by one).
02938                                                          NOTE: For power-savings, the DPRES1 is also used to
02939                                                          disable DDR1/LMC1 clocks. */
02940     uint64_t dpres0                       : 1;  /**< DDR0 Present/LMC0 Enable
02941                                                          When DPRES0 is set, LMC#0 is enabled(DDR0 pins at
02942                                                          the BOTTOM of the chip are active).
02943                                                          NOTE: When both LMC ports are enabled(DPRES1=1/DPRES0=1),
02944                                                          see XOR_BANK bit to determine how a reference is
02945                                                          assigned to a DDR/LMC port. (Also, in dual-LMC configuration,
02946                                                          the address sent to the targeted LMC port is the
02947                                                          address shifted right by one).
02948                                                          NOTE: For power-savings, the DPRES0 is also used to
02949                                                          disable DDR0/LMC0 clocks. */
02950     uint64_t dfill_dis                    : 1;  /**< L2C Dual Fill Disable
02951                                                          When set, the L2C dual-fill performance feature is
02952                                                          disabled.
02953                                                          NOTE: This bit is only intended to evaluate the
02954                                                          effectiveness of the dual-fill feature. For OPTIMAL
02955                                                          performance, this bit should ALWAYS be zero. */
02956     uint64_t fpexp                        : 4;  /**< [CYA] Forward Progress Counter Exponent
02957                                                          NOTE: Should NOT be exposed to customer! [FOR DEBUG ONLY]
02958                                                          When FPEN is enabled and the LFB is empty, the
02959                                                          forward progress counter (FPCNT) is initialized to:
02960                                                             FPCNT[24:0] = 2^(9+FPEXP)
02961                                                          When the LFB is non-empty the FPCNT is decremented
02962                                                          (every eclk interval). If the FPCNT reaches zero,
02963                                                          the LFB no longer accepts new requests until either
02964                                                             a) all of the current LFB entries have completed
02965                                                                (to ensure forward progress).
02966                                                             b) FPEMPTY=0 and another forward progress count
02967                                                                interval timeout expires.
02968                                                          EXAMPLE USE: If FPEXP=2, the FPCNT = 2048 eclks.
02969                                                          (For eclk=500MHz(2ns), this would be ~4us). */
02970     uint64_t fpempty                      : 1;  /**< [CYA] Forward Progress Counter Empty
02971                                                          NOTE: Should NOT be exposed to customer! [FOR DEBUG ONLY]
02972                                                          When set, if the forward progress counter expires,
02973                                                          all new LFB-NQs are stopped UNTIL all current LFB
02974                                                          entries have completed.
02975                                                          When clear, if the forward progress counter expires,
02976                                                          all new LFB-NQs are stopped UNTIL either
02977                                                            a) all current LFB entries have completed.
02978                                                            b) another forward progress interval expires
02979                                                          NOTE: We may want to FREEZE/HANG the system when
02980                                                          we encounter an LFB entry cannot complete, and there
02981                                                          may be times when we want to allow further LFB-NQs
02982                                                          to be permitted to help in further analyzing the
02983                                                          source */
02984     uint64_t fpen                         : 1;  /**< [CYA] Forward Progress Counter Enable
02985                                                          NOTE: Should NOT be exposed to customer! [FOR DEBUG ONLY]
02986                                                          When set, enables the Forward Progress Counter to
02987                                                          prevent new LFB entries from enqueueing until ALL
02988                                                          current LFB entries have completed. */
02989     uint64_t idxalias                     : 1;  /**< L2C Index Alias Enable
02990                                                          When set, the L2 Tag/Data Store will alias the 11-bit
02991                                                          index with the low order 11-bits of the tag.
02992                                                             index[17:7] =  (tag[28:18] ^ index[17:7])
02993                                                          NOTE: This bit must only be modified at boot time,
02994                                                          when it can be guaranteed that no blocks have been
02995                                                          loaded into the L2 Cache.
02996                                                          The index aliasing is a performance enhancement feature
02997                                                          which reduces the L2 cache thrashing experienced for
02998                                                          regular stride references.
02999                                                          NOTE: The index alias is stored in the LFB and VAB, and
03000                                                          its effects are reversed for memory references (Victims,
03001                                                          STT-Misses and Read-Misses) */
03002     uint64_t mwf_crd                      : 4;  /**< MWF Credit Threshold: When the remaining MWF credits
03003                                                          become less than or equal to the MWF_CRD, the L2C will
03004                                                          assert l2c__lmi_mwd_hiwater_a to signal the LMC to give
03005                                                          writes (victims) higher priority. */
03006     uint64_t rsp_arb_mode                 : 1;  /**< RSP Arbitration Mode:
03007                                                          - 0: Fixed Priority [HP=RFB, RMCF, RHCF, STRSP, LP=STRSC]
03008                                                          - 1: Round Robin: [RFB(reflected I/O), RMCF(RdMiss),
03009                                                              RHCF(RdHit), STRSP(ST RSP w/ invalidate),
03010                                                              STRSC(ST RSP no invalidate)] */
03011     uint64_t rfb_arb_mode                 : 1;  /**< RFB Arbitration Mode:
03012                                                          - 0: Fixed Priority -
03013                                                              IOB->PP requests are higher priority than
03014                                                              PP->IOB requests
03015                                                          - 1: Round Robin -
03016                                                              I/O requests from PP and IOB are serviced in
03017                                                              round robin */
03018     uint64_t lrf_arb_mode                 : 1;  /**< RF Arbitration Mode:
03019                                                          - 0: Fixed Priority -
03020                                                              IOB memory requests are higher priority than PP
03021                                                              memory requests.
03022                                                          - 1: Round Robin -
03023                                                              Memory requests from PP and IOB are serviced in
03024                                                              round robin. */
03025 #else
03026     uint64_t lrf_arb_mode                 : 1;
03027     uint64_t rfb_arb_mode                 : 1;
03028     uint64_t rsp_arb_mode                 : 1;
03029     uint64_t mwf_crd                      : 4;
03030     uint64_t idxalias                     : 1;
03031     uint64_t fpen                         : 1;
03032     uint64_t fpempty                      : 1;
03033     uint64_t fpexp                        : 4;
03034     uint64_t dfill_dis                    : 1;
03035     uint64_t dpres0                       : 1;
03036     uint64_t dpres1                       : 1;
03037     uint64_t xor_bank                     : 1;
03038     uint64_t lbist                        : 1;
03039     uint64_t bstrun                       : 1;
03040     uint64_t reserved_20_63               : 44;
03041 #endif
03042     } s;
03043     struct cvmx_l2c_cfg_cn30xx {
03044 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03045     uint64_t reserved_14_63               : 50;
03046     uint64_t fpexp                        : 4;  /**< [CYA] Forward Progress Counter Exponent
03047                                                          NOTE: Should NOT be exposed to customer! [FOR DEBUG ONLY]
03048                                                          When FPEN is enabled and the LFB is empty, the
03049                                                          forward progress counter (FPCNT) is initialized to:
03050                                                             FPCNT[24:0] = 2^(9+FPEXP)
03051                                                          When the LFB is non-empty the FPCNT is decremented
03052                                                          (every eclk interval). If the FPCNT reaches zero,
03053                                                          the LFB no longer accepts new requests until either
03054                                                             a) all of the current LFB entries have completed
03055                                                                (to ensure forward progress).
03056                                                             b) FPEMPTY=0 and another forward progress count
03057                                                                interval timeout expires.
03058                                                          EXAMPLE USE: If FPEXP=2, the FPCNT = 2048 eclks.
03059                                                          (For eclk=500MHz(2ns), this would be ~4us). */
03060     uint64_t fpempty                      : 1;  /**< [CYA] Forward Progress Counter Empty
03061                                                          NOTE: Should NOT be exposed to customer! [FOR DEBUG ONLY]
03062                                                          When set, if the forward progress counter expires,
03063                                                          all new LFB-NQs are stopped UNTIL all current LFB
03064                                                          entries have completed.
03065                                                          When clear, if the forward progress counter expires,
03066                                                          all new LFB-NQs are stopped UNTIL either
03067                                                            a) all current LFB entries have completed.
03068                                                            b) another forward progress interval expires
03069                                                          NOTE: We may want to FREEZE/HANG the system when
03070                                                          we encounter an LFB entry cannot complete, and there
03071                                                          may be times when we want to allow further LFB-NQs
03072                                                          to be permitted to help in further analyzing the
03073                                                          source */
03074     uint64_t fpen                         : 1;  /**< [CYA] Forward Progress Counter Enable
03075                                                          NOTE: Should NOT be exposed to customer! [FOR DEBUG ONLY]
03076                                                          When set, enables the Forward Progress Counter to
03077                                                          prevent new LFB entries from enqueueing until ALL
03078                                                          current LFB entries have completed. */
03079     uint64_t idxalias                     : 1;  /**< L2C Index Alias Enable
03080                                                          When set, the L2 Tag/Data Store will alias the 8-bit
03081                                                          index with the low order 8-bits of the tag.
03082                                                             index[14:7] =  (tag[22:15] ^ index[14:7])
03083                                                          NOTE: This bit must only be modified at boot time,
03084                                                          when it can be guaranteed that no blocks have been
03085                                                          loaded into the L2 Cache.
03086                                                          The index aliasing is a performance enhancement feature
03087                                                          which reduces the L2 cache thrashing experienced for
03088                                                          regular stride references.
03089                                                          NOTE: The index alias is stored in the LFB and VAB, and
03090                                                          its effects are reversed for memory references (Victims,
03091                                                          STT-Misses and Read-Misses) */
03092     uint64_t mwf_crd                      : 4;  /**< MWF Credit Threshold: When the remaining MWF credits
03093                                                          become less than or equal to the MWF_CRD, the L2C will
03094                                                          assert l2c__lmi_mwd_hiwater_a to signal the LMC to give
03095                                                          writes (victims) higher priority. */
03096     uint64_t rsp_arb_mode                 : 1;  /**< RSP Arbitration Mode:
03097                                                          - 0: Fixed Priority [HP=RFB, RMCF, RHCF, STRSP, LP=STRSC]
03098                                                          - 1: Round Robin: [RFB(reflected I/O), RMCF(RdMiss),
03099                                                              RHCF(RdHit), STRSP(ST RSP w/ invalidate),
03100                                                              STRSC(ST RSP no invalidate)] */
03101     uint64_t rfb_arb_mode                 : 1;  /**< RFB Arbitration Mode:
03102                                                          - 0: Fixed Priority -
03103                                                              IOB->PP requests are higher priority than
03104                                                              PP->IOB requests
03105                                                          - 1: Round Robin -
03106                                                              I/O requests from PP and IOB are serviced in
03107                                                              round robin */
03108     uint64_t lrf_arb_mode                 : 1;  /**< RF Arbitration Mode:
03109                                                          - 0: Fixed Priority -
03110                                                              IOB memory requests are higher priority than PP
03111                                                              memory requests.
03112                                                          - 1: Round Robin -
03113                                                              Memory requests from PP and IOB are serviced in
03114                                                              round robin. */
03115 #else
03116     uint64_t lrf_arb_mode                 : 1;
03117     uint64_t rfb_arb_mode                 : 1;
03118     uint64_t rsp_arb_mode                 : 1;
03119     uint64_t mwf_crd                      : 4;
03120     uint64_t idxalias                     : 1;
03121     uint64_t fpen                         : 1;
03122     uint64_t fpempty                      : 1;
03123     uint64_t fpexp                        : 4;
03124     uint64_t reserved_14_63               : 50;
03125 #endif
03126     } cn30xx;
03127     struct cvmx_l2c_cfg_cn30xx            cn31xx;
03128     struct cvmx_l2c_cfg_cn30xx            cn38xx;
03129     struct cvmx_l2c_cfg_cn30xx            cn38xxp2;
03130     struct cvmx_l2c_cfg_cn50xx {
03131 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03132     uint64_t reserved_20_63               : 44;
03133     uint64_t bstrun                       : 1;  /**< L2 Data Store Bist Running
03134                                                          Indicates when the L2C HW Bist sequence(short or long) is
03135                                                          running. [L2C ECC Bist FSM is not in the RESET/DONE state] */
03136     uint64_t lbist                        : 1;  /**< L2C Data Store Long Bist Sequence
03137                                                          When the previous state was '0' and SW writes a '1',
03138                                                          the long bist sequence (enhanced 13N March) is performed.
03139                                                          SW can then read the L2C_CFG[BSTRUN] which will indicate
03140                                                          that the long bist sequence is running. When BSTRUN-=0,
03141                                                          the state of the L2D_BST[0-3] registers contain information
03142                                                          which reflects the status of the recent long bist sequence.
03143                                                          NOTE: SW must never write LBIST=0 while Long Bist is running
03144                                                          (ie: when BSTRUN=1 never write LBIST=0). */
03145     uint64_t reserved_14_17               : 4;
03146     uint64_t fpexp                        : 4;  /**< [CYA] Forward Progress Counter Exponent
03147                                                          NOTE: Should NOT be exposed to customer! [FOR DEBUG ONLY]
03148                                                          When FPEN is enabled and the LFB is empty, the
03149                                                          forward progress counter (FPCNT) is initialized to:
03150                                                             FPCNT[24:0] = 2^(9+FPEXP)
03151                                                          When the LFB is non-empty the FPCNT is decremented
03152                                                          (every eclk interval). If the FPCNT reaches zero,
03153                                                          the LFB no longer accepts new requests until either
03154                                                             a) all of the current LFB entries have completed
03155                                                                (to ensure forward progress).
03156                                                             b) FPEMPTY=0 and another forward progress count
03157                                                                interval timeout expires.
03158                                                          EXAMPLE USE: If FPEXP=2, the FPCNT = 2048 eclks.
03159                                                          (For eclk=500MHz(2ns), this would be ~4us). */

03164                                                          entries have completed.
03165                                                          When clear, if the forward progress counter expires,
03166                                                          all new LFB-NQs are stopped UNTIL either

03168                                                            b) another forward progress interval expires

03176                                                          When set, enables the Forward Progress Counter to
03177                                                          prevent new LFB entries from enqueueing until ALL
03178                                                          current LFB entries have completed. */
03179     uint64_t idxalias                     : 1;  /**< L2C Index Alias Enable
03180                                                          When set, the L2 Tag/Data Store will alias the 7-bit
03181                                                          index with the low order 7-bits of the tag.

03183                                                          NOTE: This bit must only be modified at boot time,
03184                                                          when it can be guaranteed that no blocks have been

03192     uint64_t mwf_crd                      : 4;  /**< MWF Credit Threshold: When the remaining MWF credits

03200                                                              STRSC(ST RSP no invalidate)] */

03202                                                          - 0: Fixed Priority -
03203                                                              IOB->PP requests are higher priority than
03204                                                              PP->IOB requests
03205                                                          - 1: Round Robin -
03206                                                              I/O requests from PP and IOB are serviced in

03210                                                              IOB memory requests are higher priority than PP
03211                                                              memory requests.
03212                                                          - 1: Round Robin -
03213                                                              Memory requests from PP and IOB are serviced in
03214                                                              round robin. */
03215 #else

03436 
03437 /**
03438  * cvmx_l2c_cop0_adr
03439  *
03440  * Provides the address of the COP0 register to read/write when L2C_COP0_DAT is accessed.
03441  *
03442  * 1. RD and SEL are as defined in the description of core coprocessor 0 registers.
03443  *
03444  * 2. If the PPID is outside the range of valid cores, and not 255 (broadcast), or if
03445  * the core in question is in reset a write will be ignored and reads will timeout the
03446  * RSL bus.
03447  *
03448  * 3. If a COP0 register cannot be accessed by this mechanism the write be silently
03449  * ignored and the read data will be 0x2bad2bad2bad2bad. Otherwise, if the COP0
03450  * register doesn't exist, the read data value will be 0x000000000baddeed.
03451  */
03452 union cvmx_l2c_cop0_adr {
03453     uint64_t u64;
03454     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_adr_s {
03455 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03456     uint64_t reserved_24_63               : 40;
03457     uint64_t ppid                         : 8;  /**< Core to access; use 0xFF for broadcast write. Broadcast reads are unpredictable. */
03458     uint64_t reserved_15_15               : 1;
03459     uint64_t mbz                          : 6;  /**< Must be written to zero. */
03460     uint64_t root                         : 1;  /**< If 1, root register is accessed, if 0 guest register is accessed. */
03461     uint64_t rd                           : 5;  /**< COP0 register number. */
03462     uint64_t sel                          : 3;  /**< COP0 select. */
03463 #else
03464     uint64_t sel                          : 3;
03465     uint64_t rd                           : 5;
03466     uint64_t root                         : 1;
03467     uint64_t mbz                          : 6;
03468     uint64_t reserved_15_15               : 1;
03469     uint64_t ppid                         : 8;
03470     uint64_t reserved_24_63               : 40;
03471 #endif
03472     } s;
03473     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_adr_s            cn70xx;
03474     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_adr_s            cn70xxp1;
03475     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_adr_s            cn73xx;
03476     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_adr_s            cn78xx;
03477     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_adr_s            cn78xxp1;
03478     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_adr_s            cnf75xx;
03479 };
03480 typedef union cvmx_l2c_cop0_adr cvmx_l2c_cop0_adr_t;
03481 
03482 /**
03483  * cvmx_l2c_cop0_dat
03484  *
03485  * Provides data access for the COP0 register specified by the L2C_COP0_ADR register.
03486  *
03487  */
03488 union cvmx_l2c_cop0_dat {
03489     uint64_t u64;
03490     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_dat_s {
03491 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD

03506 /**
03507  * cvmx_l2c_cop0_map#
03508  *
03509  * L2C_COP0_MAP = PP COP0 register memory mapped region
03510  *
03511  * Description: PP COP0 register mapped region.
03512  *
03513  * NOTE: for 63xx, if the PPID is outside the range of 0-3,63 the write will be ignored and reads
03514  * will return 0x2bad2bad2bad2bad
03515  *
03516  * Notes:
03517  * (1) There are 256 COP0 registers per PP.  Registers 0-255 map to PP0's COP0 registers, 256-511 are
03518  *     mapped to PP1's, etc.  A special set X PP63 (registers 16128-16383) are for broadcast writes.
03519  *     Any write done to these registers will take effect in ALL PPs.  Note the means the L2C_COP0_MAP
03520  *     register to access can be gotten by:
03521  *
03522  *         REGNUM = [ PPID[5:0], rd[4:0], sel[2:0] ]
03523  *
03524  *     where rd and sel are as defined in the HRM description of Core Coprocessor 0 registers
03525  *     and note 4 below.
03526  *
03527  * (2) if a COP0 register cannot be accessed by this mechanism the write be silently ignored and the
03528  *     read data will be 0xBADDEED.
03529  *
03530  * (3) for 61xx, if the PPID is outside the range of 0-3,63 or if the PP in question is in reset a
03531  *     write will be ignored and reads will timeout the RSL bus.
03532  *
03533  * (4) Referring to note (1) above, the following rd/sel values are supported:
03534  *
03535  *     NOTE: Put only the "Customer type" in HRM. do not put the "Real type" in HRM.
03536  *
03537  *                    Customer                                                    Real
03538  *        rd     sel     type         Description                                 type
03539  *     ======+=======+==========+==============================================+=========
03540  *        4      2       RO          COP0 UserLocal                                RW
03541  *        7      0       RO          COP0 HWREna                                   RW
03542  *        9      0       RO          COP0 Count                                    RW
03543  *        9      6       RO          COP0 CvmCount                                 RW
03544  *        9      7       RO          COP0 CvmCtl                                   RW
03545  *       11      0       RO          COP0 Compare                                  RW
03546  *       11      6       RW          COP0 PowThrottle                              RW
03547  *       12      0       RO          COP0 Status                                   RW
03548  *       12      1       RO          COP0 IntCtl                                   RO
03549  *       12      2       RO          COP0 SRSCtl                                   RO
03550  *       13      0       RO          COP0 Cause                                    RW
03551  *       14      0       RO          COP0 EPC                                      RW
03552  *       15      0       RO          COP0 PrID                                     RO
03553  *       15      1       RO          COP0 EBase                                    RW
03554  *       16      0       RO          PC Issue Debug Info (see details below)       RO
03555  *       16      1       RO          PC Fetch Debug Info (see details below)       RO
03556  *       16      2       RO          PC Fill Debug Info (see details below)        RO
03557  *       16      3       RO          PC Misc Debug Info (see details below)        RO
03558  *       18      0       RO          COP0 WatchLo0                                 RW
03559  *       19      0       RO          COP0 WatchHi0                                 RW
03560  *       22      0       RO          COP0 MultiCoreDebug                           RW
03561  *       22      1                   COP0 VoltageMonitor                           RW
03562  *       23      0       RO          COP0 Debug                                    RW
03563  *       23      6       RO          COP0 Debug2                                   RO
03564  *       24      0       RO          COP0 DEPC                                     RW
03565  *       25      0       RO          COP0 PerfCnt Control0                         RW
03566  *       25      1       RO          COP0 PerfCnt Counter0                         RW
03567  *       25      2       RO          COP0 PerfCnt Control1                         RW
03568  *       25      3       RO          COP0 PerfCnt Counter1                         RW
03569  *       27      0       RO          COP0 CacheErr (icache)                        RW
03570  *       28      0       RO          COP0 TagLo (icache)                           RW
03571  *       28      1       RO          COP0 DataLo (icache)                          RW
03572  *       29      1       RO          COP0 DataHi (icache)                          RW
03573  *       30      0       RO          COP0 ErrorEPC                                 RW
03574  *       31      0       RO          COP0 DESAVE                                   RW
03575  *       31      2       RO          COP0 Scratch                                  RW
03576  *       31      3       RO          COP0 Scratch1                                 RW
03577  *       31      4       RO          COP0 Scratch2                                 RW
03578  *
03579  *     - PC Issue Debug Info
03580  *
03581  *       - 63:2 pc0_5a<63:2> // often VA<63:2> of the next instruction to issue
03582  *                           //    but can also be the VA of an instruction executing/replaying on pipe 0
03583  *                           //    or can also be a VA being filled into the instruction cache
03584  *                           //    or can also be unpredictable
03585  *                           // <61:49> RAZ
03586  *       1    illegal      // set when illegal VA
03587  *       0    delayslot    // set when VA is delayslot (prior branch may be either taken or not taken)
03588  *
03589  *     - PC Fetch Debug Info
03590  *
03591  *       - 63:0 fetch_address_3a // VA being fetched from the instruction cache
03592  *                               // <61:49>, <1:0> RAZ
03593  *
03594  *     - PC Fill Debug Info
03595  *
03596  *       - 63:0 fill_address_4a<63:2> // VA<63:2> being filled into instruction cache
03597  *                                    // valid when waiting_for_ifill_4a is set (see PC Misc Debug Info below)
03598  *                                    // <61:49> RAZ
03599  *          1 illegal               // set when illegal VA
03600  *          0 RAZ
03601  *
03602  *     - PC Misc Debug Info
03603  *
03604  *       - 63:3 RAZ
03605  *          2 mem_stall_3a         // stall term from L1 memory system
03606  *          1 waiting_for_pfill_4a // when waiting_for_ifill_4a is set, indicates whether instruction cache fill is due to a prefetch
03607  *          0 waiting_for_ifill_4a // set when there is an outstanding instruction cache fill
03608  */
03609 union cvmx_l2c_cop0_mapx {
03610     uint64_t u64;
03611     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_mapx_s {
03612 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03613     uint64_t data                         : 64; /**< Data to write to/read from designated PP's COP0
03614                                                          register. */
03615 #else
03616     uint64_t data                         : 64;
03617 #endif
03618     } s;
03619     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_mapx_s           cn61xx;
03620     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_mapx_s           cn63xx;
03621     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_mapx_s           cn63xxp1;
03622     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_mapx_s           cn66xx;
03623     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_mapx_s           cn68xx;
03624     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_mapx_s           cn68xxp1;
03625     struct cvmx_l2c_cop0_mapx_s           cnf71xx;
03626 };
03627 typedef union cvmx_l2c_cop0_mapx cvmx_l2c_cop0_mapx_t;

03629 /**
03630  * cvmx_l2c_ctl
03631  *
03632  * L2C_CTL = L2C Control
03633  *
03634  *
03635  * Notes:
03636  * (1) If MAXVAB is != 0, VAB_THRESH should be less than MAXVAB.
03637  *
03638  * (2) L2DFDBE and L2DFSBE allows software to generate L2DSBE, L2DDBE, VBFSBE, and VBFDBE errors for
03639  *     the purposes of testing error handling code.  When one (or both) of these bits are set a PL2
03640  *     which misses in the L2 will fill with the appropriate error in the first 2 OWs of the fill.
03641  *     Software can determine which OW pair gets the error by choosing the desired fill order
03642  *     (address<6:5>).  A PL2 which hits in the L2 will not inject any errors.  Therefore sending a
03643  *     WBIL2 prior to the PL2 is recommended to make a miss likely (if multiple processors are involved
03644  *     software must be careful to be sure no other processor or IO device can bring the block into the
03645  *     L2).
03646  *
03647  *     To generate a VBFSBE or VBFDBE, software must first get the cache block into the cache with an
03648  *     error using a PL2 which misses the L2.  Then a store partial to a portion of the cache block
03649  *     without the error must change the block to dirty.  Then, a subsequent WBL2/WBIL2/victim will
03650  *     trigger the VBFSBE/VBFDBE error.
03651  */
03652 union cvmx_l2c_ctl {
03653     uint64_t u64;
03654     struct cvmx_l2c_ctl_s {
03655 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03656     uint64_t reserved_29_63               : 35;
03657     uint64_t rdf_fast                     : 1;  /**< When 0, delay read data fifo from DCLK to RCLK by one
03658                                                          cycle.  Needed when DCLK:RCLK ratio > 3:1.  Should be
03659                                                          set before DDR traffic begins and only changed when
03660                                                          memory traffic is idle. */
03661     uint64_t disstgl2i                    : 1;  /**< Disable STGL2Is from changing the tags. */
03662     uint64_t l2dfsbe                      : 1;  /**< Force single bit ECC error on PL2 allocates (2) */
03663     uint64_t l2dfdbe                      : 1;  /**< Force double bit ECC error on PL2 allocates (2) */
03664     uint64_t discclk                      : 1;  /**< Disable conditional clocking in L2C PNR blocks. */
03665     uint64_t maxvab                       : 4;  /**< Maximum VABs in use at once
03666                                                          (0 means 16, 1-15 as expected) */
03667     uint64_t maxlfb                       : 4;  /**< Maximum LFBs in use at once
03668                                                          (0 means 16, 1-15 as expected) */
03669     uint64_t rsp_arb_mode                 : 1;  /**< Arbitration mode for RSC/RSD bus. 0 = round-robin; 1 = static priority.
03670                                                          1. IOR data.
03671                                                          2. STIN/FILLs.
03672                                                          3. STDN/SCDN/SCFL. */
03673     uint64_t xmc_arb_mode                 : 1;  /**< Arbitration mode for ADD bus QOS queues. 0 = fully determined through QOS, 1 = QOS0
03674                                                          highest priority; QOS 1-7 use normal mode. */
03675     uint64_t reserved_2_13                : 12;
03676     uint64_t disecc                       : 1;  /**< Tag and data ECC disable. */
03677     uint64_t disidxalias                  : 1;  /**< Index alias disable. */
03678 #else
03679     uint64_t disidxalias                  : 1;
03680     uint64_t disecc                       : 1;
03681     uint64_t reserved_2_13                : 12;
03682     uint64_t xmc_arb_mode                 : 1;
03683     uint64_t rsp_arb_mode                 : 1;
03684     uint64_t maxlfb                       : 4;
03685     uint64_t maxvab                       : 4;
03686     uint64_t discclk                      : 1;
03687     uint64_t l2dfdbe                      : 1;
03688     uint64_t l2dfsbe                      : 1;
03689     uint64_t disstgl2i                    : 1;
03690     uint64_t rdf_fast                     : 1;
03691     uint64_t reserved_29_63               : 35;
03692 #endif
03693     } s;

03720                                                          Specifies the number of cycles after the first LMC
03721                                                          fill cycle to wait before requesting a fill on the
03722                                                          RSC/RSD bus.

03724                                                            // by the time we start counting)

03728                                                            // stay in the same position

03732                                                            ef_cnt = ef_cnt + 2;
03733                                                            // - 3 rclks to recognize first write
03734                                                            ef_cnt = ef_cnt - 3;

03736                                                            ef_cnt = ef_cnt + 3;

03742                                                          L2C increases the priority of all writes in the LMC. */

03908                                                          == 1, QOS0 highest priority, QOS1-7 use normal mode */
03909     uint64_t ef_ena                       : 1;  /**< LMC early fill enable */
03910     uint64_t ef_cnt                       : 7;  /**< LMC early fill count
03911                                                          Specifies the number of cycles after the first LMC
03912                                                          fill cycle to wait before requesting a fill on the
03913                                                          RSC/RSD bus.
03914                                                            // 7 dclks (we've received 1st out of 8
03915                                                            // by the time we start counting)
03916                                                            ef_cnt = (7 * dclk0_period) / rclk_period;
03917                                                            // + 1 rclk if the dclk and rclk edges don't
03918                                                            // stay in the same position
03919                                                            if ((dclk0_gen.period % rclk_gen.period) != 0)
03920                                                               ef_cnt = ef_cnt + 1;
03921                                                            // + 2 rclk synchronization uncertainty
03922                                                            ef_cnt = ef_cnt + 2;
03923                                                            // - 3 rclks to recognize first write
03924                                                            ef_cnt = ef_cnt - 3;
03925                                                            // + 3 rclks to perform first write
03926                                                            ef_cnt = ef_cnt + 3;
03927                                                            // - 9 rclks minimum latency from counter expire
03928                                                            // to final fbf read
03929                                                            ef_cnt = ef_cnt - 9; */
03930     uint64_t vab_thresh                   : 4;  /**< VAB Threshold
03931                                                          When the number of valid VABs exceeds this number the
03932                                                          L2C increases the priority of all writes in the LMC. */
03933     uint64_t disecc                       : 1;  /**< Tag and Data ECC Disable */
03934     uint64_t disidxalias                  : 1;  /**< Index Alias Disable */
03935 #else
03936     uint64_t disidxalias                  : 1;
03937     uint64_t disecc                       : 1;
03938     uint64_t vab_thresh                   : 4;
03939     uint64_t ef_cnt                       : 7;
03940     uint64_t ef_ena                       : 1;
03941     uint64_t xmc_arb_mode                 : 1;
03942     uint64_t rsp_arb_mode                 : 1;
03943     uint64_t maxlfb                       : 4;
03944     uint64_t maxvab                       : 4;
03945     uint64_t discclk                      : 1;
03946     uint64_t l2dfdbe                      : 1;
03947     uint64_t l2dfsbe                      : 1;
03948     uint64_t disstgl2i                    : 1;
03949     uint64_t rdf_fast                     : 1;
03950     uint64_t sepcmt                       : 1;
03951     uint64_t reserved_30_63               : 34;
03952 #endif
03953     } cn68xx;

03959     uint64_t reserved_28_28               : 1;

04043 
04044 /**
04045  * cvmx_l2c_dbg
04046  *
04047  * L2C_DBG = L2C DEBUG Register
04048  *
04049  * Description: L2C Tag/Data Store Debug Register
04050  *
04051  * Notes:
04052  * (1) When using the L2T, L2D or FINV Debug probe feature, the LDD command WILL NOT update the DuTags.
04053  * (2) L2T, L2D, FINV MUST BE mutually exclusive (only one set)
04054  * (3) Force Invalidate is intended as a means for SW to invalidate the L2 Cache while also writing back
04055  *     dirty data to memory to maintain coherency.
04056  * (4) L2 Cache Lock Down feature MUST BE disabled (L2C_LCKBASE[LCK_ENA]=0) if ANY of the L2C debug
04057  *     features (L2T, L2D, FINV) are enabled.
04058  */
04059 union cvmx_l2c_dbg {
04060     uint64_t u64;
04061     struct cvmx_l2c_dbg_s {
04062 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04063     uint64_t reserved_15_63               : 49;
04064     uint64_t lfb_enum                     : 4;  /**< Specifies the LFB Entry# which is to be captured. */
04065     uint64_t lfb_dmp                      : 1;  /**< LFB Dump Enable: When written(=1), the contents of
04066                                                          the LFB specified by LFB_ENUM[3:0] are captured
04067                                                          into the L2C_LFB(0/1/2) registers.
04068                                                          NOTE: Some fields of the LFB entry are unpredictable
04069                                                          and dependent on usage. This is only intended to be
04070                                                          used for HW debug. */
04071     uint64_t ppnum                        : 4;  /**< When L2C_DBG[L2T] or L2C_DBG[L2D] or L2C_DBG[FINV]
04072                                                          is enabled, this field determines which one-of-16
04073                                                          PPs is selected as the diagnostic PP. */
04074     uint64_t set                          : 3;  /**< When L2C_DBG[L2T] or L2C_DBG[L2D] or L2C_DBG[FINV]
04075                                                          is enabled, this field determines 1-of-n targeted
04076                                                          sets to act upon.
04077                                                          NOTE: L2C_DBG[SET] must never equal a crippled or
04078                                                          unusable set (see UMSK* registers and Cripple mode
04079                                                          fuses). */
04080     uint64_t finv                         : 1;  /**< Flush-Invalidate.
04081                                                          When flush-invalidate is enable (FINV=1), all STF
04082                                                          (L1 store-miss) commands generated from the diagnostic PP
04083                                                          (L2C_DBG[PPNUM]) will invalidate the specified set
04084                                                          (L2C_DBG[SET]) at the index specified in the STF
04085                                                          address[17:7]. If a dirty block is detected (D=1), it is
04086                                                          written back to memory. The contents of the invalid
04087                                                          L2 Cache line is also 'scrubbed' with the STF write data.
04088                                                          NOTE: If L2C_CFG[IDXALIAS]=1, the index specified in
04089                                                          STF address[17:7] refers to the 'aliased' address.
04090                                                          NOTE: An STF command with write data=ZEROES can be
04091                                                          generated by SW using the Prefetch instruction with
04092                                                          Hint=30d "prepare for Store", followed by a SYNCW.
04093                                                          What is seen at the L2C as an STF w/wrdcnt=0 with all
04094                                                          of its mask bits clear (indicates zero-fill data).
04095                                                          A flush-invalidate will 'force-hit' the L2 cache at
04096                                                          [index,set] and invalidate the entry (V=0/D=0/L=0/U=0).
04097                                                          If the cache block is dirty, it is also written back
04098                                                          to memory. The DuTag state is probed/updated as normal
04099                                                          for an STF request.
04100                                                          TYPICAL APPLICATIONS:
04101                                                             1) L2 Tag/Data ECC SW Recovery
04102                                                             2) Cache Unlocking
04103                                                          NOTE: If the cacheline had been previously LOCKED(L=1),
04104                                                          a flush-invalidate operation will explicitly UNLOCK
04105                                                          (L=0) the set/index specified.
04106                                                          NOTE: The diagnostic PP cores can generate STF
04107                                                          commands to the L2 Cache whenever all 128 bytes in a
04108                                                          block are written. SW must take this into consideration
04109                                                          to avoid 'errant' Flush-Invalidates. */
04110     uint64_t l2d                          : 1;  /**< When enabled (and L2C_DBG[L2T]=0), fill data is
04111                                                          returned directly from the L2 Data Store
04112                                                          (regardless of hit/miss) when an LDD(L1 load-miss) command
04113                                                          is issued from a PP determined by the L2C_DBG[PPNUM]
04114                                                          field. The selected set# is determined by the
04115                                                          L2C_DBG[SET] field, and the index is determined
04116                                                          from the address[17:7] associated with the LDD
04117                                                          command.
04118                                                          This 'force-hit' will NOT alter the current L2 Tag
04119                                                          state OR the DuTag state. */
04120     uint64_t l2t                          : 1;  /**< When enabled, L2 Tag information [V,D,L,U,phys_addr[33:18]]
04121                                                          is returned on the data bus starting at +32(and +96) bytes
04122                                                          offset from the beginning of cacheline when an LDD
04123                                                          (L1 load-miss) command is issued from a PP determined by
04124                                                          the L2C_DBG[PPNUM] field.
04125                                                          The selected L2 set# is determined by the L2C_DBG[SET]
04126                                                          field, and the L2 index is determined from the
04127                                                          phys_addr[17:7] associated with the LDD command.
04128                                                          This 'L2 force-hit' will NOT alter the current L2 Tag
04129                                                          state OR the DuTag state.
04130                                                          NOTE: The diagnostic PP should issue a d-stream load
04131                                                          to an aligned cacheline+0x20(+0x60) in order to have the
04132                                                          return VDLUTAG information (in OW2/OW6) written directly
04133                                                          into the proper PP register. The diagnostic PP should also
04134                                                          flush it's local L1 cache after use(to ensure data
04135                                                          coherency).
04136                                                          NOTE: The position of the VDLUTAG data in the destination
04137                                                          register is dependent on the endian mode(big/little).
04138                                                          NOTE: N3K-Pass2 modification. (This bit's functionality
04139                                                          has changed since Pass1-in the following way).
04140                                                          NOTE: (For L2C BitMap testing of L2 Data Store OW ECC):
04141                                                          If L2D_ERR[ECC_ENA]=0, the OW ECC from the selected
04142                                                          half cacheline (see: L2D_ERR[BMHCLSEL] is also
04143                                                          conditionally latched into the L2D_FSYN0/1 CSRs if an
04144                                                          LDD command is detected from the diagnostic PP(L2C_DBG[PPNUM]). */
04145 #else
04146     uint64_t l2t                          : 1;
04147     uint64_t l2d                          : 1;
04148     uint64_t finv                         : 1;
04149     uint64_t set                          : 3;
04150     uint64_t ppnum                        : 4;
04151     uint64_t lfb_dmp                      : 1;
04152     uint64_t lfb_enum                     : 4;
04153     uint64_t reserved_15_63               : 49;
04154 #endif
04155     } s;

04307                                                          L2C_DBG[PPNUM] field. The selected set# is determined
04308                                                          by the L2C_DBG[SET] field, and the index is determined
04309                                                          from the address[15:7] associated with the LDD command.
04310                                                          This 'L2 force-hit' will NOT alter the current L2 Tag
04311                                                          state OR the DuTag state. */
04312     uint64_t l2t                          : 1;  /**< When enabled, L2 Tag information [V,D,L,U,phys_addr[33:16]]
04313                                                          is returned on the data bus starting at +32(and +96) bytes
04314                                                          offset from the beginning of cacheline when an LDD
04315                                                          (L1 load-miss) command is issued from a PP determined by
04316                                                          the L2C_DBG[PPNUM] field.
04317                                                          The selected L2 set# is determined by the L2C_DBG[SET]
04318                                                          field, and the L2 index is determined from the
04319                                                          phys_addr[15:7] associated with the LDD command.
04320                                                          This 'L2 force-hit' will NOT alter the current L2 Tag
04321                                                          state OR the DuTag state.
04322                                                          NOTE: The diagnostic PP should issue a d-stream load
04323                                                          to an aligned cacheline+0x20(+0x60) in order to have the
04324                                                          return VDLUTAG information (in OW2/OW6) written directly
04325                                                          into the proper PP register. The diagnostic PP should also
04326                                                          flush it's local L1 cache after use(to ensure data
04327                                                          coherency).
04328                                                          NOTE: The position of the VDLUTAG data in the destination
04329                                                          register is dependent on the endian mode(big/little).
04330                                                          NOTE: (For L2C BitMap testing of L2 Data Store OW ECC):
04331                                                          If L2D_ERR[ECC_ENA]=0, the OW ECC from the selected
04332                                                          half cacheline (see: L2D_ERR[BMHCLSEL] is also
04333                                                          conditionally latched into the L2D_FSYN0/1 CSRs if an
04334                                                          LDD(L1 load-miss) is detected from the diagnostic PP
04335                                                          (L2C_DBG[PPNUM]). */
04336 #else

04356                                                          the LFB specified by LFB_ENUM[2:0] are captured

04370                                                          fuses). */

04372                                                          When flush-invalidate is enable (FINV=1), all STF
04373                                                          (L1 store-miss) commands generated from the diagnostic PP
04374                                                          (L2C_DBG[PPNUM]) will invalidate the specified set
04375                                                          (L2C_DBG[SET]) at the index specified in the STF
04376                                                          address[13:7]. If a dirty block is detected (D=1), it is

04378                                                          L2 Cache line is also 'scrubbed' with the STF write data.

04395                                                          a flush-invalidate operation will explicitly UNLOCK

04400                                                          to avoid 'errant' Flush-Invalidates. */

04549 /**
04550  * cvmx_l2c_dut
04551  *
04552  * L2C_DUT = L2C DUTAG Register
04553  *
04554  * Description: L2C Duplicate Tag State Register
04555  *
04556  * Notes:
04557  * (1) When using the L2T, L2D or FINV Debug probe feature, an LDD command issued by the diagnostic PP
04558  *     WILL NOT update the DuTags.
04559  * (2) L2T, L2D, FINV MUST BE mutually exclusive (only one enabled at a time).
04560  * (3) Force Invalidate is intended as a means for SW to invalidate the L2 Cache while also writing back
04561  *     dirty data to memory to maintain coherency. (A side effect of FINV is that an LDD L2 fill is
04562  *     launched which fills data into the L2 DS).
04563  */
04564 union cvmx_l2c_dut {
04565     uint64_t u64;
04566     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_s {
04567 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04568     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
04569     uint64_t dtena                        : 1;  /**< DuTag Diagnostic read enable.
04570                                                          When L2C_DUT[DTENA]=1, all LDD(L1 load-miss)
04571                                                          commands issued from the diagnostic PP
04572                                                          (L2C_DBG[PPNUM]) will capture the DuTag state (V|L1TAG)
04573                                                          of the PP#(specified in the LDD address[29:26] into
04574                                                          the L2C_DUT CSR register. This allows the diagPP to
04575                                                          read ALL DuTags (from any PP).
04576                                                          The DuTag Set# to capture is extracted from the LDD
04577                                                          address[25:20]. The diagnostic PP would issue the
04578                                                          LDD then read the L2C_DUT register (one at a time).
04579                                                          This LDD 'L2 force-hit' will NOT alter the current L2
04580                                                          Tag State OR the DuTag state.
04581                                                          NOTE: For CN58XX the DuTag SIZE has doubled (to 16KB)
04582                                                          where each DuTag is organized as 2x 64-way entries.
04583                                                          The LDD address[7] determines which 1(of-2) internal
04584                                                          64-ways to select.
04585                                                          The fill data is returned directly from the L2 Data
04586                                                          Store(regardless of hit/miss) when an LDD command
04587                                                          is issued from a PP determined by the L2C_DBG[PPNUM]
04588                                                          field. The selected L2 Set# is determined by the
04589                                                          L2C_DBG[SET] field, and the index is determined
04590                                                          from the address[17:7] associated with the LDD
04591                                                          command.
04592                                                          This 'L2 force-hit' will NOT alter the current L2 Tag
04593                                                          state OR the DuTag state.
04594                                                          NOTE: In order for the DiagPP to generate an LDD command
04595                                                          to the L2C, it must first force an L1 Dcache flush. */
04596     uint64_t reserved_30_30               : 1;
04597     uint64_t dt_vld                       : 1;  /**< Duplicate L1 Tag Valid bit latched in for previous
04598                                                          LDD(L1 load-miss) command sourced by diagnostic PP. */
04599     uint64_t dt_tag                       : 29; /**< Duplicate L1 Tag[35:7] latched in for previous
04600                                                          LDD(L1 load-miss) command sourced by diagnostic PP. */
04601 #else
04602     uint64_t dt_tag                       : 29;
04603     uint64_t dt_vld                       : 1;
04604     uint64_t reserved_30_30               : 1;
04605     uint64_t dtena                        : 1;
04606     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
04607 #endif
04608     } s;
04609     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_s                 cn30xx;
04610     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_s                 cn31xx;
04611     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_s                 cn38xx;
04612     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_s                 cn38xxp2;
04613     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_s                 cn50xx;
04614     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_s                 cn52xx;
04615     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_s                 cn52xxp1;

04623 /**
04624  * cvmx_l2c_dut_map#
04625  *
04626  * L2C_DUT_MAP = L2C DUT memory map region
04627  *
04628  * Description: Address of the start of the region mapped to the duplicate tag.  Can be used to read
04629  * and write the raw duplicate tag CAM.  Writes should be used only with great care as they can easily
04630  * destroy the coherency of the memory system.  In any case this region is expected to only be used
04631  * for debug.
04632  *
04633  * This base address should be combined with PP virtual ID, L1 way and L1 set to produce the final
04634  * address as follows:
04635  *     addr<63:13>      L2C_DUT_MAP<63:13>
04636  *     addr<12:11>      PP VID
04637  *     addr<10:6>       L1 way
04638  *     addr<5:3>        L1 set
04639  *     addr<2:0>        UNUSED
04640  *
04641  * Notes:
04642  * (1) The tag is 37:10 from the 38-bit OCTEON physical address after hole removal. (The hole is between DR0
04643  * and DR1. Remove the hole by subtracting 256MB from 38-bit OCTEON L2/DRAM physical addresses >= 512 MB.)
04644  */
04645 union cvmx_l2c_dut_mapx {
04646     uint64_t u64;
04647     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_mapx_s {
04648 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04649     uint64_t reserved_38_63               : 26;
04650     uint64_t tag                          : 28; /**< The tag value (see Note 1) */
04651     uint64_t reserved_1_9                 : 9;
04652     uint64_t valid                        : 1;  /**< The valid bit */
04653 #else
04654     uint64_t valid                        : 1;
04655     uint64_t reserved_1_9                 : 9;
04656     uint64_t tag                          : 28;
04657     uint64_t reserved_38_63               : 26;
04658 #endif
04659     } s;
04660     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_mapx_s            cn61xx;
04661     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_mapx_s            cn63xx;
04662     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_mapx_s            cn63xxp1;
04663     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_mapx_s            cn66xx;
04664     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_mapx_s            cn68xx;
04665     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_mapx_s            cn68xxp1;
04666     struct cvmx_l2c_dut_mapx_s            cnf71xx;
04667 };
04668 typedef union cvmx_l2c_dut_mapx cvmx_l2c_dut_mapx_t;

04670 /**
04671  * cvmx_l2c_ecc_ctl
04672  *
04673  * Flip ECC bits to generate single-bit or double-bit ECC errors in all instances of a given
04674  * memory type. Encodings are as follows.
04675  * 0x0 = No error.
04676  * 0x1 = Single-bit error on ECC<0>.
04677  * 0x2 = Single-bit error on ECC<1>.
04678  * 0x3 = Double-bit error on ECC<1:0>.
04679  *
04680  * L2DFLIP allows software to generate L2DSBE, L2DDBE, VBFSBE, and VBFDBE errors for the purposes
04681  * of testing error handling code. When one (or both) of these bits are set, a PL2 that misses in
04682  * the L2 will fill with the appropriate error in the first two OWs of the fill. Software can
04683  * determine which OW pair gets the error by choosing the desired fill order (address<6:5>). A
04684  * PL2 that hits in the L2 will not inject any errors. Therefore sending a WBIL2 prior to the PL2
04685  * is recommended to make a miss likely. (If multiple processors are involved, software must be
04686  * sure that no other processor or I/O device can bring the block into the L2).
04687  *
04688  * To generate a VBFSBE or VBFDBE, software must first get the cache block into the cache with an
04689  * error using a PL2 that misses the L2. Then a store partial to a portion of the cache block
04690  * without the error must change the block to dirty. Then, a subsequent WBL2/WBIL2/victim will
04691  * trigger the VBFSBE/VBFDBE error.
04692  */
04693 union cvmx_l2c_ecc_ctl {
04694     uint64_t u64;
04695     struct cvmx_l2c_ecc_ctl_s {
04696 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04697     uint64_t reserved_12_63               : 52;
04698     uint64_t mibflip                      : 2;  /**< Reserved. */
04699     uint64_t l2dflip                      : 2;  /**< Generate an ECC error in the L2D. See note above. */
04700     uint64_t l2tflip                      : 2;  /**< Generate an ECC error in the L2T. */
04701     uint64_t rdfflip                      : 2;  /**< Generate an ECC error in RDF memory. */
04702     uint64_t xmdflip                      : 2;  /**< Generate an ECC error in all corresponding CBC XMD memories. */
04703     uint64_t ioccmdflip                   : 2;  /**< Generate an ECC error in all corresponding IOCCMD memories. */
04704 #else
04705     uint64_t ioccmdflip                   : 2;
04706     uint64_t xmdflip                      : 2;
04707     uint64_t rdfflip                      : 2;
04708     uint64_t l2tflip                      : 2;
04709     uint64_t l2dflip                      : 2;
04710     uint64_t mibflip                      : 2;
