04757 /**
04758  * cvmx_l2c_err_tdt#
04759  *
04760  * L2C_ERR_TDT = L2C TAD DaTa Error Info
04761  *
04762  *
04763  * Notes:
04764  * (1) If the status bit corresponding to the value of the TYPE field is not set the WAYIDX/SYN fields
04765  *     are not associated with the errors currently logged by the status bits and should be ignored.
04766  *     This can occur, for example, because of a race between a write to clear a DBE and a new, lower
04767  *     priority, SBE error occuring.  If the SBE arrives prior to the DBE clear the WAYIDX/SYN fields
04768  *     will still be locked, but the new SBE error status bit will still be set.
04769  *
04770  * (2) The four types of errors have differing priorities.  Priority (from lowest to highest) is SBE,
04771  *     VSBE, DBE, VDBE.  A error will lock the WAYIDX, and SYN fields for other errors of equal or
04772  *     lower priority until cleared by software.  This means that the error information is always
04773  *     (assuming the TYPE field matches) for the highest priority error logged in the status bits.
04774  *
04775  * (3) If VSBE or VDBE are set (and the TYPE field matches), the WAYIDX fields are valid and the
04776  *     syndrome can be found in L2C_ERR_VBF.
04777  *
04778  * (4) The syndrome is recorded for DBE errors, though the utility of the value is not clear.
04779  */
04780 union cvmx_l2c_err_tdtx {
04781     uint64_t u64;
04782     struct cvmx_l2c_err_tdtx_s {
04783 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04784     uint64_t dbe                          : 1;  /**< L2D Double-Bit error has occurred */

04786     uint64_t vdbe                         : 1;  /**< VBF Double-Bit error has occurred */
04787     uint64_t vsbe                         : 1;  /**< VBF Single-Bit error has occurred */
04788     uint64_t syn                          : 10; /**< L2D syndrome (valid only for SBE/DBE, not VSBE/VDBE) */
04789     uint64_t reserved_22_49               : 28;
04790     uint64_t wayidx                       : 18; /**< Way, index, OW of the L2 block containing the error */
04791     uint64_t reserved_2_3                 : 2;
04792     uint64_t type                         : 2;  /**< The type of error the WAYIDX,SYN were latched for.
04793                                                          0 - VSBE
04794                                                          1 - VDBE
04795                                                          2 - SBE
04796                                                          3 - DBE */
04797 #else
04798     uint64_t type                         : 2;
04799     uint64_t reserved_2_3                 : 2;
04800     uint64_t wayidx                       : 18;
04801     uint64_t reserved_22_49               : 28;
04802     uint64_t syn                          : 10;
04803     uint64_t vsbe                         : 1;
04804     uint64_t vdbe                         : 1;
04805     uint64_t sbe                          : 1;
04806     uint64_t dbe                          : 1;
04807 #endif
04808     } s;
04809     struct cvmx_l2c_err_tdtx_cn61xx {
04810 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04811     uint64_t dbe                          : 1;  /**< L2D Double-Bit error has occurred */

04813     uint64_t vdbe                         : 1;  /**< VBF Double-Bit error has occurred */
04814     uint64_t vsbe                         : 1;  /**< VBF Single-Bit error has occurred */

04818     uint64_t reserved_2_3                 : 2;

04820                                                          0 - VSBE
04821                                                          1 - VDBE
04822                                                          2 - SBE
04823                                                          3 - DBE */
04824 #else
04825     uint64_t type                         : 2;
04826     uint64_t reserved_2_3                 : 2;
04827     uint64_t wayidx                       : 16;
04828     uint64_t reserved_20_49               : 30;
04829     uint64_t syn                          : 10;
04830     uint64_t vsbe                         : 1;
04831     uint64_t vdbe                         : 1;

04834 #endif
04835     } cn61xx;
04836     struct cvmx_l2c_err_tdtx_cn63xx {

04839     uint64_t sbe                          : 1;  /**< L2D Single-Bit error has occurred */

04841     uint64_t vsbe                         : 1;  /**< VBF Single-Bit error has occurred */

04871 /**
04872  * cvmx_l2c_err_ttg#
04873  *
04874  * L2C_ERR_TTG = L2C TAD TaG Error Info
04875  *
04876  *
04877  * Notes:
04878  * (1) The priority of errors (highest to lowest) is DBE, SBE, NOWAY.  An error will lock the SYN, and
04879  *     WAYIDX fields for equal or lower priority errors until cleared by software.
04880  *
04881  * (2) The syndrome is recorded for DBE errors, though the utility of the value is not clear.
04882  *
04883  * (3) A NOWAY error does not change the value of the SYN field, and leaves WAYIDX[20:17]
04884  *     unpredictable.  WAYIDX[16:7] is the L2 block index associated with the command which had no way
04885  *     to allocate.
04886  *
04887  * (4) If the status bit corresponding to the value of the TYPE field is not set the WAYIDX/SYN fields
04888  *     are not associated with the errors currently logged by the status bits and should be ignored.
04889  *     This can occur, for example, because of a race between a write to clear a DBE and a new, lower
04890  *     priority, SBE error occuring.  If the SBE arrives prior to the DBE clear the WAYIDX/SYN fields
04891  *     will still be locked, but the new SBE error status bit will still be set.
04892  */
04893 union cvmx_l2c_err_ttgx {
04894     uint64_t u64;
04895     struct cvmx_l2c_err_ttgx_s {
04896 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04897     uint64_t dbe                          : 1;  /**< Double-Bit ECC error */
04898     uint64_t sbe                          : 1;  /**< Single-Bit ECC error */
04899     uint64_t noway                        : 1;  /**< No way was available for allocation.
04900                                                          L2C sets NOWAY during its processing of a
04901                                                          transaction whenever it needed/wanted to allocate
04902                                                          a WAY in the L2 cache, but was unable to. NOWAY==1
04903                                                          is (generally) not an indication that L2C failed to
04904                                                          complete transactions. Rather, it is a hint of
04905                                                          possible performance degradation. (For example, L2C
04906                                                          must read-modify-write DRAM for every transaction
04907                                                          that updates some, but not all, of the bytes in a
04908                                                          cache block, misses in the L2 cache, and cannot
04909                                                          allocate a WAY.) There is one "failure" case where
04910                                                          L2C will set NOWAY: when it cannot leave a block
04911                                                          locked in the L2 cache as part of a LCKL2
04912                                                          transaction. */
04913     uint64_t reserved_56_60               : 5;
04914     uint64_t syn                          : 6;  /**< Syndrome for the single-bit error */
04915     uint64_t reserved_22_49               : 28;
04916     uint64_t wayidx                       : 15; /**< Way and index of the L2 block containing the error */
04917     uint64_t reserved_2_6                 : 5;
04918     uint64_t type                         : 2;  /**< The type of error the WAYIDX,SYN were latched for.
04919                                                          0 - not valid
04920                                                          1 - NOWAY
04921                                                          2 - SBE
04922                                                          3 - DBE */
04923 #else
04924     uint64_t type                         : 2;
04925     uint64_t reserved_2_6                 : 5;
04926     uint64_t wayidx                       : 15;
04927     uint64_t reserved_22_49               : 28;
04928     uint64_t syn                          : 6;
04929     uint64_t reserved_56_60               : 5;
04930     uint64_t noway                        : 1;
04931     uint64_t sbe                          : 1;
04932     uint64_t dbe                          : 1;
04933 #endif
04934     } s;
04935     struct cvmx_l2c_err_ttgx_cn61xx {
04936 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04937     uint64_t dbe                          : 1;  /**< Double-Bit ECC error */
04938     uint64_t sbe                          : 1;  /**< Single-Bit ECC error */
04939     uint64_t noway                        : 1;  /**< No way was available for allocation.
04940                                                          L2C sets NOWAY during its processing of a
04941                                                          transaction whenever it needed/wanted to allocate
04942                                                          a WAY in the L2 cache, but was unable to. NOWAY==1
04943                                                          is (generally) not an indication that L2C failed to
04944                                                          complete transactions. Rather, it is a hint of
04945                                                          possible performance degradation. (For example, L2C
04946                                                          must read-modify-write DRAM for every transaction
04947                                                          that updates some, but not all, of the bytes in a
04948                                                          cache block, misses in the L2 cache, and cannot
04949                                                          allocate a WAY.) There is one "failure" case where
04950                                                          L2C will set NOWAY: when it cannot leave a block

04952                                                          transaction. */
04953     uint64_t reserved_56_60               : 5;

04956     uint64_t wayidx                       : 13; /**< Way and index of the L2 block containing the error */
04957     uint64_t reserved_2_6                 : 5;

04959                                                          0 - not valid

05023 /**
05024  * cvmx_l2c_err_vbf#
05025  *
05026  * L2C_ERR_VBF = L2C VBF Error Info
05027  *
05028  *
05029  * Notes:
05030  * (1) The way/index information is stored in L2C_ERR_TDT, assuming no later interrupt occurred to
05031  *     overwrite the information.  See the notes associated with L2C_ERR_TDT for full details.
05032  *
05033  * (2) The first VSBE will lock the register for other VSBE's.  A VDBE, however, will overwrite a
05034  *     previously logged VSBE.  Once a VDBE has been logged all later errors will not be logged.  This
05035  *     means that if VDBE is set the information in the register is for the VDBE, if VDBE is clear and
05036  *     VSBE is set the register contains information about the VSBE.
05037  *
05038  * (3) The syndrome is recorded for VDBE errors, though the utility of the value is not clear.
05039  *
05040  * (4) If the status bit corresponding to the value of the TYPE field is not set the SYN field is not
05041  *     associated with the errors currently logged by the status bits and should be ignored.  This can
05042  *     occur, for example, because of a race between a write to clear a VDBE and a new, lower priority,
05043  *     VSBE error occuring.  If the VSBE arrives prior to the VDBE clear the SYN field will still be
05044  *     locked, but the new VSBE error status bit will still be set.
05045  */
05046 union cvmx_l2c_err_vbfx {
05047     uint64_t u64;
05048     struct cvmx_l2c_err_vbfx_s {
05049 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05050     uint64_t reserved_62_63               : 2;
05051     uint64_t vdbe                         : 1;  /**< VBF Double-Bit error has occurred */
05052     uint64_t vsbe                         : 1;  /**< VBF Single-Bit error has occurred */
05053     uint64_t vsyn                         : 10; /**< VBF syndrome (valid only if VSBE/VDBE is set) */
05054     uint64_t reserved_2_49                : 48;
05055     uint64_t type                         : 2;  /**< The type of error the SYN were latched for.
05056                                                          0 - VSBE
05057                                                          1 - VDBE */
05058 #else
05059     uint64_t type                         : 2;
05060     uint64_t reserved_2_49                : 48;
05061     uint64_t vsyn                         : 10;
05062     uint64_t vsbe                         : 1;
05063     uint64_t vdbe                         : 1;
05064     uint64_t reserved_62_63               : 2;
05065 #endif
05066     } s;
05067     struct cvmx_l2c_err_vbfx_s            cn61xx;
05068     struct cvmx_l2c_err_vbfx_s            cn63xx;
05069     struct cvmx_l2c_err_vbfx_s            cn63xxp1;
05070     struct cvmx_l2c_err_vbfx_s            cn66xx;
05071     struct cvmx_l2c_err_vbfx_s            cn68xx;
05072     struct cvmx_l2c_err_vbfx_s            cn68xxp1;
05073     struct cvmx_l2c_err_vbfx_s            cnf71xx;

05077 /**
05078  * cvmx_l2c_err_xmc
05079  *
05080  * L2C_ERR_XMC = L2C XMC request error
05081  *
05082  * Description: records error information for HOLE*, BIG* and VRT* interrupts.
05083  *
05084  * Notes:
05085  * (1) The first BIGWR/HOLEWR/VRT* interrupt will lock the register until L2C_INT_REG[6:1] are
05086  *     cleared.
05087  *
05088  * (2) ADDR<15:0> will always be zero for VRT* interrupts.
05089  *
05090  * (3) ADDR is the 38-bit OCTEON physical address after hole removal. (The hole is between DR0
05091  *     and DR1. Remove the hole by subtracting 256MB from all 38-bit OCTEON L2/DRAM physical addresses
05092  *     >= 512 MB.)
05093  *
05094  * (4) For 63xx pass 2.0 and all 68xx ADDR<15:0> will ALWAYS be zero.
05095  */
05096 union cvmx_l2c_err_xmc {

05098     struct cvmx_l2c_err_xmc_s {
05099 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05100     uint64_t cmd                          : 6;  /**< XMC command or request causing error
05101                                                          TRA_FILT_CMD indicates encoding */
05102     uint64_t reserved_54_57               : 4;
05103     uint64_t sid                          : 6;  /**< XMC sid of request causing error
05104                                                          0-3      => selects a cnMIPS core
05105                                                          else if a STF/STT/STP:
05106                                                           8,9     => FPA, TIM, HFA, USB, PCIe, MIX, DPI,
05107                                                                      BOOTDMA, ZIP, RAD, or POW
05108                                                           0xA     => IOB DWB engine
05109                                                           0xC,0xD => PIP/IPD
05110                                                          else (if a read/fill):
05111                                                           8       => FPA, TIM, HFA, USB, PCIe, MIX, DPI,
05112                                                                      BOOTDMA, ZIP, RAD, or POW
05113                                                           9       => PKO */
05114     uint64_t reserved_38_47               : 10;
05115     uint64_t addr                         : 38; /**< XMC address causing the error (see Notes 2 and 3) */
05116 #else
05117     uint64_t addr                         : 38;
05118     uint64_t reserved_38_47               : 10;
05119     uint64_t sid                          : 6;
05120     uint64_t reserved_54_57               : 4;
05121     uint64_t cmd                          : 6;
05122 #endif
05123     } s;
05124     struct cvmx_l2c_err_xmc_cn61xx {
05125 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05126     uint64_t cmd                          : 6;  /**< XMC command or request causing error
05127                                                          TRA_FILT_CMD indicates encoding */
05128     uint64_t reserved_52_57               : 6;
05129     uint64_t sid                          : 4;  /**< XMC sid of request causing error
05130                                                          0-3      => selects a cnMIPS core
05131                                                          else if a STF/STT/STP:
05132                                                           8,9     => FPA, TIM, HFA, USB, PCIe, MIX, DPI,
05133                                                                      BOOTDMA, ZIP, RAD, or POW
05134                                                           0xA     => IOB DWB engine
05135                                                           0xC,0xD => PIP/IPD
05136                                                          else (if a read/fill):
05137                                                           8       => FPA, TIM, HFA, USB, PCIe, MIX, DPI,
05138                                                                      BOOTDMA, ZIP, RAD, or POW
05139                                                           9       => PKO */
05140     uint64_t reserved_38_47               : 10;
05141     uint64_t addr                         : 38; /**< XMC address causing the error (see Notes 2 and 3) */
05142 #else
05143     uint64_t addr                         : 38;

05149     } cn61xx;

05184 /**
05185  * cvmx_l2c_grpwrr0
05186  *
05187  * L2C_GRPWRR0 = L2C PP Weighted Round \#0 Register
05188  *
05189  * Description: Defines Weighted rounds(32) for Group PLC0,PLC1
05190  *
05191  * Notes:
05192  * - Starvation of a group 'could' occur, unless SW takes the precaution to ensure that each GROUP
05193  * participates in at least 1(of 32) rounds (ie: At least 1 bit(of 32) should be clear).
05194  */
05195 union cvmx_l2c_grpwrr0 {
05196     uint64_t u64;
05197     struct cvmx_l2c_grpwrr0_s {

05199     uint64_t plc1rmsk                     : 32; /**< PLC1 Group#1 Weighted Round Mask
05200                                                          Each bit represents 1 of 32 rounds
05201                                                          for Group \#1's participation. When a 'round' bit is
05202                                                          set, Group#1 is 'masked' and DOES NOT participate.
05203                                                          When a 'round' bit is clear, Group#1 WILL
05204                                                          participate in the arbitration for this round. */
05205     uint64_t plc0rmsk                     : 32; /**< PLC Group#0 Weighted Round Mask
05206                                                          Each bit represents 1 of 32 rounds
05207                                                          for Group \#0's participation. When a 'round' bit is
05208                                                          set, Group#0 is 'masked' and DOES NOT participate.
05209                                                          When a 'round' bit is clear, Group#0 WILL
05210                                                          participate in the arbitration for this round. */
05211 #else
05212     uint64_t plc0rmsk                     : 32;
05213     uint64_t plc1rmsk                     : 32;
05214 #endif
05215     } s;
05216     struct cvmx_l2c_grpwrr0_s             cn52xx;
05217     struct cvmx_l2c_grpwrr0_s             cn52xxp1;

05507 /**
05508  * cvmx_l2c_int_stat
05509  *
05510  * L2C_INT_STAT = L2C Global Interrupt Status Register
05511  *
05512  * Description:
05513  */
05514 union cvmx_l2c_int_stat {
05515     uint64_t u64;
05516     struct cvmx_l2c_int_stat_s {
05517 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05518     uint64_t reserved_9_63                : 55;
05519     uint64_t lck2                         : 1;  /**< HW detected a case where a Rd/Wr Miss from PP#n
05520                                                          could not find an available/unlocked set (for
05521                                                          replacement).
05522                                                          Most likely, this is a result of SW mixing SET
05523                                                          PARTITIONING with ADDRESS LOCKING. If SW allows
05524                                                          another PP to LOCKDOWN all SETs available to PP#n,
05525                                                          then a Rd/Wr Miss from PP#n will be unable
05526                                                          to determine a 'valid' replacement set (since LOCKED
05527                                                          addresses should NEVER be replaced).
05528                                                          If such an event occurs, the HW will select the smallest
05529                                                          available SET(specified by UMSK'x)' as the replacement
05530                                                          set, and the address is unlocked.
05531                                                          NOTE: This is the 'same' bit as L2T_ERR[LCKERR2] */
05532     uint64_t lck                          : 1;  /**< SW attempted to LOCK DOWN the last available set of
05533                                                          the INDEX (which is ignored by HW - but reported to SW).
05534                                                          The LDD(L1 load-miss) for the LOCK operation is completed
05535                                                          successfully, however the address is NOT locked.
05536                                                          NOTE: 'Available' sets takes the L2C_SPAR*[UMSK*]
05537                                                          into account. For example, if diagnostic PPx has
05538                                                          UMSKx defined to only use SETs [1:0], and SET1 had
05539                                                          been previously LOCKED, then an attempt to LOCK the
05540                                                          last available SET0 would result in a LCKERR. (This
05541                                                          is to ensure that at least 1 SET at each INDEX is
05542                                                          not LOCKED for general use by other PPs).
05543                                                          NOTE: This is the 'same' bit as L2T_ERR[LCKERR] */
05544     uint64_t l2dded                       : 1;  /**< L2D Double Error detected (DED)
05545                                                          NOTE: This is the 'same' bit as L2D_ERR[DED_ERR] */
05546     uint64_t l2dsec                       : 1;  /**< L2D Single Error corrected (SEC)
05547                                                          NOTE: This is the 'same' bit as L2D_ERR[SEC_ERR] */
05548     uint64_t l2tded                       : 1;  /**< L2T Double Bit Error detected (DED)
05549                                                          During every L2 Tag Probe, all 8 sets Tag's (at a
05550                                                          given index) are checked for double bit errors(DBEs).
05551                                                          This bit is set if ANY of the 8 sets contains a DBE.
05552                                                          DBEs also generated an interrupt(if enabled).
05553                                                          NOTE: This is the 'same' bit as L2T_ERR[DED_ERR] */
05554     uint64_t l2tsec                       : 1;  /**< L2T Single Bit Error corrected (SEC) status
05555                                                          During every L2 Tag Probe, all 8 sets Tag's (at a
05556                                                          given index) are checked for single bit errors(SBEs).
05557                                                          This bit is set if ANY of the 8 sets contains an SBE.
05558                                                          SBEs are auto corrected in HW and generate an
05559                                                          interrupt(if enabled).
05560                                                          NOTE: This is the 'same' bit as L2T_ERR[SEC_ERR] */
05561     uint64_t oob3                         : 1;  /**< DMA Out of Bounds Interrupt Status Range#3 */
05562     uint64_t oob2                         : 1;  /**< DMA Out of Bounds Interrupt Status Range#2 */
05563     uint64_t oob1                         : 1;  /**< DMA Out of Bounds Interrupt Status Range#1 */
05564 #else
05565     uint64_t oob1                         : 1;
05566     uint64_t oob2                         : 1;
05567     uint64_t oob3                         : 1;
05568     uint64_t l2tsec                       : 1;
05569     uint64_t l2tded                       : 1;
05570     uint64_t l2dsec                       : 1;
05571     uint64_t l2dded                       : 1;
05572     uint64_t lck                          : 1;
05573     uint64_t lck2                         : 1;
05574     uint64_t reserved_9_63                : 55;
05575 #endif
05576     } s;
05577     struct cvmx_l2c_int_stat_s            cn52xx;
05578     struct cvmx_l2c_int_stat_s            cn52xxp1;

05667 /**
05668  * cvmx_l2c_lckbase
05669  *
05670  * L2C_LCKBASE = L2C LockDown Base Register
05671  *
05672  * Description: L2C LockDown Base Register
05673  *
05674  * Notes:
05675  * (1) SW RESTRICTION \#1: SW must manage the L2 Data Store lockdown space such that at least 1
05676  *     set per cache line remains in the 'unlocked' (normal) state to allow general caching operations.
05677  *     If SW violates this restriction, a status bit is set (LCK_ERR) and an interrupt is posted.
05678  *     [this limits the total lockdown space to 7/8ths of the total L2 data store = 896KB]
05679  * (2) IOB initiated LDI commands are ignored (only PP initiated LDI/LDD commands are considered
05680  *     for lockdown).
05681  * (3) To 'unlock' a locked cache line, SW can use the FLUSH-INVAL CSR mechanism (see L2C_DBG[FINV]).
05682  * (4) LCK_ENA MUST only be activated when debug modes are disabled (L2C_DBG[L2T], L2C_DBG[L2D], L2C_DBG[FINV]).
05683  */
05684 union cvmx_l2c_lckbase {
05685     uint64_t u64;
05686     struct cvmx_l2c_lckbase_s {
05687 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05688     uint64_t reserved_31_63               : 33;
05689     uint64_t lck_base                     : 27; /**< Base Memory block address[33:7]. Specifies the
05690                                                          starting address of the lockdown region. */
05691     uint64_t reserved_1_3                 : 3;
05692     uint64_t lck_ena                      : 1;  /**< L2 Cache Lock Enable
05693                                                          When the LCK_ENA=1, all LDI(I-stream Load) or
05694                                                          LDD(L1 load-miss) commands issued from the
05695                                                          diagnostic PP (specified by the L2C_DBG[PPNUM]),
05696                                                          which fall within a predefined lockdown address
05697                                                          range (specified by: [lck_base:lck_base+lck_offset])
05698                                                          are LOCKED in the L2 cache. The LOCKED state is
05699                                                          denoted using an explicit L2 Tag bit (L=1).
05700                                                          If the LOCK request L2-Hits (on ANY SET), then data is
05701                                                          returned from the L2 and the hit set is updated to the
05702                                                          LOCKED state. NOTE: If the Hit Set# is outside the
05703                                                          available sets for a given PP (see UMSK'x'), the
05704                                                          the LOCK bit is still SET. If the programmer's intent
05705                                                          is to explicitly LOCK addresses into 'available' sets,
05706                                                          care must be taken to flush-invalidate the cache first
05707                                                          (to avoid such situations). Not following this procedure
05708                                                          can lead to LCKERR2 interrupts.
05709                                                          If the LOCK request L2-Misses, a replacment set is
05710                                                          chosen(from the available sets (UMSK'x').
05711                                                          If the replacement set contains a dirty-victim it is
05712                                                          written back to memory. Memory read data is then written
05713                                                          into the replacement set, and the replacment SET is
05714                                                          updated to the LOCKED state(L=1).
05715                                                          NOTE: SETs that contain LOCKED addresses are
05716                                                          excluded from the replacement set selection algorithm.
05717                                                          NOTE: The LDD command will allocate the DuTag as normal.
05718                                                          NOTE: If L2C_CFG[IDXALIAS]=1, the address is 'aliased' first
05719                                                          before being checked against the lockdown address
05720                                                          range. To ensure an 'aliased' address is properly locked,
05721                                                          it is recommmended that SW preload the 'aliased' locked adddress
05722                                                          into the L2C_LCKBASE[LCK_BASE] register (while keeping
05723                                                          L2C_LCKOFF[LCK_OFFSET]=0).
05724                                                          NOTE: The OCTEON(N3) implementation only supports 16GB(MAX) of
05725                                                          physical memory. Therefore, only byte address[33:0] are used
05726                                                          (ie: address[35:34] are ignored). */
05727 #else
05728     uint64_t lck_ena                      : 1;
05729     uint64_t reserved_1_3                 : 3;
05730     uint64_t lck_base                     : 27;
05731     uint64_t reserved_31_63               : 33;
05732 #endif
05733     } s;
05734     struct cvmx_l2c_lckbase_s             cn30xx;
05735     struct cvmx_l2c_lckbase_s             cn31xx;
05736     struct cvmx_l2c_lckbase_s             cn38xx;
05737     struct cvmx_l2c_lckbase_s             cn38xxp2;
05738     struct cvmx_l2c_lckbase_s             cn50xx;
05739     struct cvmx_l2c_lckbase_s             cn52xx;
05740     struct cvmx_l2c_lckbase_s             cn52xxp1;
05741     struct cvmx_l2c_lckbase_s             cn56xx;
05742     struct cvmx_l2c_lckbase_s             cn56xxp1;
05743     struct cvmx_l2c_lckbase_s             cn58xx;
05744     struct cvmx_l2c_lckbase_s             cn58xxp1;
05745 };
05746 typedef union cvmx_l2c_lckbase cvmx_l2c_lckbase_t;
05747 
05748 /**
05749  * cvmx_l2c_lckoff
05750  *
05751  * L2C_LCKOFF = L2C LockDown OFFSET Register
05752  *
05753  * Description: L2C LockDown OFFSET Register
05754  *
05755  * Notes:
05756  * (1) The generation of the end lockdown block address will 'wrap'.

05765                                                          the ending block address of the lockdown
05766                                                          region:
05767                                                          End Lockdown block Address[33:7] =
05768                                                          LCK_BASE[33:7]+LCK_OFFSET[9:0] */
05769 #else
05770     uint64_t lck_offset                   : 10;
05771     uint64_t reserved_10_63               : 54;
05772 #endif
05773     } s;

06225 /**
06226  * cvmx_l2c_mci#_err
06227  *
06228  * This register records error information for all MCI errors.
06229  * An error locks [VBF4], [INDEX], [SYN0], and [SYN1] and sets the bit corresponding to the error
06230  * received. VBFDBE errors take priority and will overwrite an earlier logged VBFSBE error. The
06231  * information from exactly one VBF read is present at any given time and serves to document
06232  * which error(s) were present in the read with the highest priority error.
06233  * The syndrome is recorded for DBE errors, though the utility of the value is not clear.
06234  */
06235 union cvmx_l2c_mcix_err {
06236     uint64_t u64;
06237     struct cvmx_l2c_mcix_err_s {
06238 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06239     uint64_t vbfdbe1                      : 1;  /**< INDEX/SYN1 corresponds to a double-bit VBF ECC error. */
06240     uint64_t vbfdbe0                      : 1;  /**< INDEX/SYN0 corresponds to a double-bit VBF ECC error. */
06241     uint64_t vbfsbe1                      : 1;  /**< INDEX/SYN1 corresponds to a single-bit VBF ECC error. */
06242     uint64_t vbfsbe0                      : 1;  /**< INDEX/SYN0 corresponds to a single-bit VBF ECC error. */
06243     uint64_t reserved_48_59               : 12;
06244     uint64_t syn1                         : 8;  /**< Error syndrome for QW1 (<127:64>). */
06245     uint64_t syn0                         : 8;  /**< Error syndrome for QW0 (<63:0>). */
06246     uint64_t reserved_12_31               : 20;
06247     uint64_t vbf4                         : 1;  /**< When 1, errors were from VBF (4+a), when 0, from VBF (0+a). */
06248     uint64_t index                        : 7;  /**< VBF index which was read and had the error(s). */
06249     uint64_t reserved_0_3                 : 4;
06250 #else
06251     uint64_t reserved_0_3                 : 4;
06252     uint64_t index                        : 7;
06253     uint64_t vbf4                         : 1;
06254     uint64_t reserved_12_31               : 20;
06255     uint64_t syn0                         : 8;
06256     uint64_t syn1                         : 8;
06257     uint64_t reserved_48_59               : 12;
06258     uint64_t vbfsbe0                      : 1;
06259     uint64_t vbfsbe1                      : 1;
06260     uint64_t vbfdbe0                      : 1;
06261     uint64_t vbfdbe1                      : 1;
06262 #endif
06263     } s;
06264     struct cvmx_l2c_mcix_err_s            cn70xx;
06265     struct cvmx_l2c_mcix_err_s            cn70xxp1;
06266     struct cvmx_l2c_mcix_err_s            cn73xx;
06267     struct cvmx_l2c_mcix_err_s            cn78xx;
06268     struct cvmx_l2c_mcix_err_s            cn78xxp1;
06269     struct cvmx_l2c_mcix_err_s            cnf75xx;
06270 };
06271 typedef union cvmx_l2c_mcix_err cvmx_l2c_mcix_err_t;

06413                                                          L2C_INT_STAT[OOB*] CSRs and the DMA store WILL
06414                                                          NOT occur. If the corresponding L2C_INT_EN[OOB*]
06415                                                          is enabled, an interrupt will also be reported. */

06429 /**
06430  * cvmx_l2c_oob1
06431  *
06432  * L2C_OOB1 = L2C Out of Bounds Range Checker
06433  *
06434  * Description: Defines DMA "Out of Bounds" region \#1. If a DMA initiated write transaction generates an address
06435  * within the specified region, the write is 'ignored' and an interrupt is generated to alert software.
06436  */
06437 union cvmx_l2c_oob1 {
06438     uint64_t u64;
06439     struct cvmx_l2c_oob1_s {
06440 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06441     uint64_t fadr                         : 27; /**< DMA initated Memory Range Checker Failing Address
06442                                                          When L2C_INT_STAT[OOB1]=1, this field indicates the
06443                                                          DMA cacheline address.
06444                                                          (addr[33:7] = full cacheline address captured)
06445                                                          NOTE: FADR is locked down until L2C_INT_STAT[OOB1]
06446                                                          is cleared. */
06447     uint64_t fsrc                         : 1;  /**< DMA Out of Bounds Failing Source Command
06448                                                          When L2C_INT_STAT[OOB1]=1, this field indicates the
06449                                                          type of DMA command.
06450                                                           - 0: ST* (STF/P/T)
06451                                                           - 1: DWB (Don't WriteBack)
06452                                                          NOTE: FSRC is locked down until L2C_INT_STAT[OOB1]
06453                                                          is cleared. */
06454     uint64_t reserved_34_35               : 2;
06455     uint64_t sadr                         : 14; /**< DMA initated Memory Range Checker Starting Address
06456                                                          (1MB granularity) */
06457     uint64_t reserved_14_19               : 6;
06458     uint64_t size                         : 14; /**< DMA Out of Bounds Range Checker Size
06459                                                          (1MB granularity)
06460                                                          Example: 0: 0MB / 1: 1MB
06461                                                          The range check is for:
06462                                                              (SADR<<20) <= addr[33:0] < (((SADR+SIZE) & 0x3FFF)<<20)
06463                                                          SW NOTE: SADR+SIZE could be setup to potentially wrap
06464                                                          the 34bit ending bounds address. */
06465 #else
06466     uint64_t size                         : 14;
06467     uint64_t reserved_14_19               : 6;
06468     uint64_t sadr                         : 14;
06469     uint64_t reserved_34_35               : 2;
06470     uint64_t fsrc                         : 1;
06471     uint64_t fadr                         : 27;
06472 #endif
06473     } s;
06474     struct cvmx_l2c_oob1_s                cn52xx;
06475     struct cvmx_l2c_oob1_s                cn52xxp1;
06476     struct cvmx_l2c_oob1_s                cn56xx;
06477     struct cvmx_l2c_oob1_s                cn56xxp1;
06478 };
06479 typedef union cvmx_l2c_oob1 cvmx_l2c_oob1_t;

06513                                                          The range check is for:

06617 /**
06618  * cvmx_l2c_pfctl
06619  *
06620  * L2C_PFCTL = L2 Performance Counter Control Register
06621  *
06622  * Description: Controls the actions of the 4 Performance Counters
06623  *
06624  * Notes:
06625  * - There are four 36b performance counter registers which can simultaneously count events.
06626  * Each Counter's event is programmably selected via the corresponding CNTxSEL field:
06627  *       CNTxSEL[5:0]    Event
06628  *    -----------------+-----------------------
06629  *             0       | Cycles
06630  *             1       | L2 LDI Command Miss (NOTE: Both PP and IOB are cabable of generating LDI)
06631  *             2       | L2 LDI Command Hit  (NOTE: Both PP and IOB are cabable of generating LDI)
06632  *             3       | L2 non-LDI Command Miss
06633  *             4       | L2 non-LDI Command Hit
06634  *             5       | L2 Miss (total)
06635  *             6       | L2 Hit (total)
06636  *             7       | L2 Victim Buffer Hit (Retry Probe)
06637  *             8       | LFB-NQ Index Conflict
06638  *             9       | L2 Tag Probe (issued - could be VB-Retried)
06639  *            10       | L2 Tag Update (completed - note: some CMD types do not update)
06640  *            11       | L2 Tag Probe Completed (beyond VB-RTY window)
06641  *            12       | L2 Tag Dirty Victim
06642  *            13       | L2 Data Store NOP
06643  *            14       | L2 Data Store READ
06644  *            15       | L2 Data Store WRITE
06645  *            16       | Memory Fill Data valid (1 strobe/32B)
06646  *            17       | Memory Write Request
06647  *            18       | Memory Read Request
06648  *            19       | Memory Write Data valid (1 strobe/32B)
06649  *            20       | XMC NOP (XMC Bus Idle)
06650  *            21       | XMC LDT (Load-Through Request)
06651  *            22       | XMC LDI (L2 Load I-Stream Request)
06652  *            23       | XMC LDD (L2 Load D-stream Request)
06653  *            24       | XMC STF (L2 Store Full cacheline Request)
06654  *            25       | XMC STT (L2 Store Through Request)
06655  *            26       | XMC STP (L2 Store Partial Request)
06656  *            27       | XMC STC (L2 Store Conditional Request)
06657  *            28       | XMC DWB (L2 Don't WriteBack Request)
06658  *            29       | XMC PL2 (L2 Prefetch Request)
06659  *            30       | XMC PSL1 (L1 Prefetch Request)
06660  *            31       | XMC IOBLD
06661  *            32       | XMC IOBST
06662  *            33       | XMC IOBDMA
06663  *            34       | XMC IOBRSP
06664  *            35       | XMD Bus valid (all)
06665  *            36       | XMD Bus valid (DST=L2C) Memory Data
06666  *            37       | XMD Bus valid (DST=IOB) REFL Data
06667  *            38       | XMD Bus valid (DST=PP) IOBRSP Data
06668  *            39       | RSC NOP
06669  *            40       | RSC STDN
06670  *            41       | RSC FILL
06671  *            42       | RSC REFL
06672  *            43       | RSC STIN
06673  *            44       | RSC SCIN
06674  *            45       | RSC SCFL
06675  *            46       | RSC SCDN
06676  *            47       | RSD Data Valid
06677  *            48       | RSD Data Valid (FILL)
06678  *            49       | RSD Data Valid (STRSP)
06679  *            50       | RSD Data Valid (REFL)
06680  *            51       | LRF-REQ (LFB-NQ)
06681  *            52       | DT RD-ALLOC (LDD/PSL1 Commands)
06682  *            53       | DT WR-INVAL (ST* Commands)
06683  */
06684 union cvmx_l2c_pfctl {
06685     uint64_t u64;
06686     struct cvmx_l2c_pfctl_s {
06687 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
06688     uint64_t reserved_36_63               : 28;
06689     uint64_t cnt3rdclr                    : 1;  /**< Performance Counter 3 Read Clear
06690                                                          When set, all CSR reads of the L2C_PFC3
06691                                                          register will auto-clear the counter. This allows
06692                                                          SW to maintain 'cumulative' counters in SW.
06693                                                          NOTE: If the CSR read occurs in the same cycle as
06694                                                          the 'event' to be counted, the counter will
06695                                                          properly reflect the event. */
06696     uint64_t cnt2rdclr                    : 1;  /**< Performance Counter 2 Read Clear
06697                                                          When set, all CSR reads of the L2C_PFC2
06698                                                          register will auto-clear the counter. This allows
06699                                                          SW to maintain 'cumulative' counters in SW.
06700                                                          NOTE: If the CSR read occurs in the same cycle as
06701                                                          the 'event' to be counted, the counter will
06702                                                          properly reflect the event. */
06703     uint64_t cnt1rdclr                    : 1;  /**< Performance Counter 1 Read Clear
06704                                                          When set, all CSR reads of the L2C_PFC1
06705                                                          register will auto-clear the counter. This allows
06706                                                          SW to maintain 'cumulative' counters in SW.
06707                                                          NOTE: If the CSR read occurs in the same cycle as
06708                                                          the 'event' to be counted, the counter will
06709                                                          properly reflect the event. */
06710     uint64_t cnt0rdclr                    : 1;  /**< Performance Counter 0 Read Clear
06711                                                          When set, all CSR reads of the L2C_PFC0
06712                                                          register will 'auto-clear' the counter. This allows
06713                                                          SW to maintain accurate 'cumulative' counters.
06714                                                          NOTE: If the CSR read occurs in the same cycle as
06715                                                          the 'event' to be counted, the counter will
06716                                                          properly reflect the event. */
06717     uint64_t cnt3ena                      : 1;  /**< Performance Counter 3 Enable
06718                                                          When this bit is set, the performance counter
06719                                                          is enabled. */
06720     uint64_t cnt3clr                      : 1;  /**< Performance Counter 3 Clear
06721                                                          When the CSR write occurs, if this bit is set,
06722                                                          the performance counter is cleared. Otherwise,
06723                                                          it will resume counting from its current value. */
06724     uint64_t cnt3sel                      : 6;  /**< Performance Counter 3 Event Selector
06725                                                          (see list of selectable events to count in NOTES) */
06726     uint64_t cnt2ena                      : 1;  /**< Performance Counter 2 Enable
06727                                                          When this bit is set, the performance counter
06728                                                          is enabled. */
06729     uint64_t cnt2clr                      : 1;  /**< Performance Counter 2 Clear
06730                                                          When the CSR write occurs, if this bit is set,
06731                                                          the performance counter is cleared. Otherwise,
06732                                                          it will resume counting from its current value. */
06733     uint64_t cnt2sel                      : 6;  /**< Performance Counter 2 Event Selector
06734                                                          (see list of selectable events to count in NOTES) */
06735     uint64_t cnt1ena                      : 1;  /**< Performance Counter 1 Enable
06736                                                          When this bit is set, the performance counter
06737                                                          is enabled. */
06738     uint64_t cnt1clr                      : 1;  /**< Performance Counter 1 Clear
06739                                                          When the CSR write occurs, if this bit is set,
06740                                                          the performance counter is cleared. Otherwise,
06741                                                          it will resume counting from its current value. */
06742     uint64_t cnt1sel                      : 6;  /**< Performance Counter 1 Event Selector
06743                                                          (see list of selectable events to count in NOTES) */
06744     uint64_t cnt0ena                      : 1;  /**< Performance Counter 0 Enable
06745                                                          When this bit is set, the performance counter
06746                                                          is enabled. */
06747     uint64_t cnt0clr                      : 1;  /**< Performance Counter 0 Clear
06748                                                          When the CSR write occurs, if this bit is set,
06749                                                          the performance counter is cleared. Otherwise,
06750                                                          it will resume counting from its current value. */
06751     uint64_t cnt0sel                      : 6;  /**< Performance Counter 0 Event Selector
06752                                                          (see list of selectable events to count in NOTES) */
06753 #else
06754     uint64_t cnt0sel                      : 6;
06755     uint64_t cnt0clr                      : 1;
06756     uint64_t cnt0ena                      : 1;
06757     uint64_t cnt1sel                      : 6;
06758     uint64_t cnt1clr                      : 1;
06759     uint64_t cnt1ena                      : 1;
06760     uint64_t cnt2sel                      : 6;
06761     uint64_t cnt2clr                      : 1;
06762     uint64_t cnt2ena                      : 1;
06763     uint64_t cnt3sel                      : 6;
06764     uint64_t cnt3clr                      : 1;
06765     uint64_t cnt3ena                      : 1;
06766     uint64_t cnt0rdclr                    : 1;
06767     uint64_t cnt1rdclr                    : 1;
06768     uint64_t cnt2rdclr                    : 1;
06769     uint64_t cnt3rdclr                    : 1;
06770     uint64_t reserved_36_63               : 28;
06771 #endif
06772     } s;
06773     struct cvmx_l2c_pfctl_s               cn30xx;
06774     struct cvmx_l2c_pfctl_s               cn31xx;
06775     struct cvmx_l2c_pfctl_s               cn38xx;
06776     struct cvmx_l2c_pfctl_s               cn38xxp2;
06777     struct cvmx_l2c_pfctl_s               cn50xx;
06778     struct cvmx_l2c_pfctl_s               cn52xx;
06779     struct cvmx_l2c_pfctl_s               cn52xxp1;
06780     struct cvmx_l2c_pfctl_s               cn56xx;
06781     struct cvmx_l2c_pfctl_s               cn56xxp1;
06782     struct cvmx_l2c_pfctl_s               cn58xx;
06783     struct cvmx_l2c_pfctl_s               cn58xxp1;
06784 };

07061 /**
07062  * cvmx_l2c_rtg#_err
07063  *
07064  * This register records error information for all RTG SBE/DBE errors.
07065  * The priority of errors (lowest to highest) is SBE, DBE. An error locks [SYN], [WAY],
07066  * and [L2IDX] fields for equal or lower priority errors until cleared by software.
07067  * The syndrome is recorded for DBE errors, though the utility of the value is not clear.
07068  * [L2IDX][19:7] is the L2 block index associated with the command which had no way to allocate.
07069  */
07070 union cvmx_l2c_rtgx_err {
07071     uint64_t u64;
07072     struct cvmx_l2c_rtgx_err_s {
07073 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07074     uint64_t rtgdbe                       : 1;  /**< Information refers to a double-bit RTG ECC error. */
07075     uint64_t rtgsbe                       : 1;  /**< Information refers to a single-bit RTG ECC error. */
07076     uint64_t reserved_39_61               : 23;
07077     uint64_t syn                          : 7;  /**< Syndrome for the single-bit error. */
07078     uint64_t reserved_24_31               : 8;
07079     uint64_t way                          : 4;  /**< Way of the L2 block containing the error */
07080     uint64_t l2idx                        : 13; /**< Index of the L2 block containing the error */
07081     uint64_t reserved_0_6                 : 7;
07082 #else
07083     uint64_t reserved_0_6                 : 7;
07084     uint64_t l2idx                        : 13;
07085     uint64_t way                          : 4;
07086     uint64_t reserved_24_31               : 8;
07087     uint64_t syn                          : 7;
07088     uint64_t reserved_39_61               : 23;
07089     uint64_t rtgsbe                       : 1;
07090     uint64_t rtgdbe                       : 1;
07091 #endif
07092     } s;
07093     struct cvmx_l2c_rtgx_err_s            cn78xx;
07094 };
07095 typedef union cvmx_l2c_rtgx_err cvmx_l2c_rtgx_err_t;

07097 /**
07098  * cvmx_l2c_spar0
07099  *
07100  * L2C_SPAR0 = L2 Set Partitioning Register (PP0-3)
07101  *
07102  * Description: L2 Set Partitioning Register
07103  *
07104  * Notes:
07105  * - When a bit is set in the UMSK'x' register, a memory command issued from PP='x' will NOT select that
07106  *   set for replacement.
07107  * - There MUST ALWAYS BE at least 1 bit clear in each UMSK'x' register for proper L2 cache operation
07108  * - NOTES: When L2C FUSE[136] is blown(CRIP_256K), then SETS#7-4 are SET in all UMSK'x' registers
07109  *          When L2C FUSE[137] is blown(CRIP_128K), then SETS#7-2 are SET in all UMSK'x' registers
07110  */
07111 union cvmx_l2c_spar0 {

07113     struct cvmx_l2c_spar0_s {
07114 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD

07118     uint64_t umsk1                        : 8;  /**< PP[1] L2 'DO NOT USE' set partition mask */
07119     uint64_t umsk0                        : 8;  /**< PP[0] L2 'DO NOT USE' set partition mask */
07120 #else
07121     uint64_t umsk0                        : 8;
07122     uint64_t umsk1                        : 8;
07123     uint64_t umsk2                        : 8;
07124     uint64_t umsk3                        : 8;
07125     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
07126 #endif
07127     } s;
07128     struct cvmx_l2c_spar0_cn30xx {
07129 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07130     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
07131     uint64_t umsk0                        : 4;  /**< PP[0] L2 'DO NOT USE' set partition mask */
07132 #else
07133     uint64_t umsk0                        : 4;
07134     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
07135 #endif
07136     } cn30xx;
07137     struct cvmx_l2c_spar0_cn31xx {
07138 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07139     uint64_t reserved_12_63               : 52;
07140     uint64_t umsk1                        : 4;  /**< PP[1] L2 'DO NOT USE' set partition mask */
07141     uint64_t reserved_4_7                 : 4;
07142     uint64_t umsk0                        : 4;  /**< PP[0] L2 'DO NOT USE' set partition mask */
07143 #else
07144     uint64_t umsk0                        : 4;
07145     uint64_t reserved_4_7                 : 4;

07147     uint64_t reserved_12_63               : 52;
07148 #endif

07157 #else
07158     uint64_t umsk0                        : 8;

07160     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
07161 #endif
07162     } cn50xx;

07469 /**

07471  *
07472  * This register records error information for BIG* interrupts. The BIG logic only
07473  * applies to local addresses. The first BIGWR error will lock the register until the
07474  * logged error type is cleared; BIGRD never locks the register.

07486                                                          unpredictable. */

07490                                                          (if enabled). (The hole is between DR0 and DR1. Remove the hole by subtracting
07491                                                          256MB from all L2/DRAM physical addresses >= 512 MB.) */

07673     uint64_t reserved_18_31               : 14;
07674     uint64_t lfbto                        : 1;  /**< An LFB entry (or more) has encountered a timeout condition When LFBTO timeout condition
07675                                                          occurs L2C_TAD()_TIMEOUT is loaded. L2C_TAD()_TIMEOUT is loaded with info from the
07676                                                          first LFB that timed out. if multiple LFB timed out simultaneously, then the it will
07677                                                          capture info from the lowest LFB number that timed out. */
07678     uint64_t reserved_15_16               : 2;
07679     uint64_t bigrd                        : 1;  /**< Read reference past L2C_BIG_CTL[MAXDRAM] occurred. [BIGRD] interrupts can occur during
07680                                                          normal operation as the cores are allowed to prefetch to nonexistent memory locations.
07681                                                          Therefore, [BIGRD] is for informational purposes only. See L2C_TAD()_ERR for logged
07682                                                          information. */
07683     uint64_t bigwr                        : 1;  /**< Write reference past L2C_BIG_CTL[MAXDRAM] occurred. See L2C_TAD()_ERR for logged information. */
07684     uint64_t holerd                       : 1;  /**< Read reference to 256MB hole occurred. */
07685     uint64_t holewr                       : 1;  /**< Write reference to 256MB hole occurred. */
07686     uint64_t reserved_2_10                : 9;
07687     uint64_t l2ddbe                       : 1;  /**< L2D double-bit error occurred. See L2C_TQD()_ERR for logged information. */
07688     uint64_t l2dsbe                       : 1;  /**< L2D single-bit error occurred. See L2C_TQD()_ERR for logged information. */
07689 #else

07702     uint64_t rddisoci                     : 1;
07703     uint64_t wrdisoci                     : 1;
07704     uint64_t reserved_36_63               : 28;
07705 #endif
07706     } s;
07707     struct cvmx_l2c_tadx_int_cn61xx {
07708 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
07709     uint64_t reserved_9_63                : 55;
07710     uint64_t wrdislmc                     : 1;  /**< Illegal Write to Disabled LMC Error
07711                                                          A DRAM write arrived before the LMC(s) were enabled */
07712     uint64_t rddislmc                     : 1;  /**< Illegal Read  to Disabled LMC Error
07713                                                          A DRAM read  arrived before the LMC(s) were enabled */
07714     uint64_t noway                        : 1;  /**< No way available interrupt
07715                                                          Shadow copy of L2C_ERR_TTGX[NOWAY]
07716                                                          Writes of 1 also clear L2C_ERR_TTGX[NOWAY] */

07718                                                          Shadow copy of L2C_ERR_TDTX[VDBE]

07720     uint64_t vbfsbe                       : 1;  /**< VBF Single-Bit Error
07721                                                          Shadow copy of L2C_ERR_TDTX[VSBE]
07722                                                          Writes of 1 also clear L2C_ERR_TDTX[VSBE] */
07723     uint64_t tagdbe                       : 1;  /**< TAG Double-Bit Error
07724                                                          Shadow copy of L2C_ERR_TTGX[DBE]

07726     uint64_t tagsbe                       : 1;  /**< TAG Single-Bit Error
07727                                                          Shadow copy of L2C_ERR_TTGX[SBE]
07728                                                          Writes of 1 also clear L2C_ERR_TTGX[SBE] */
07729     uint64_t l2ddbe                       : 1;  /**< L2D Double-Bit Error
07730                                                          Shadow copy of L2C_ERR_TDTX[DBE]
07731                                                          Writes of 1 also clear L2C_ERR_TDTX[DBE] */
07732     uint64_t l2dsbe                       : 1;  /**< L2D Single-Bit Error
07733                                                          Shadow copy of L2C_ERR_TDTX[SBE]
07734                                                          Writes of 1 also clear L2C_ERR_TDTX[SBE] */
07735 #else
07736     uint64_t l2dsbe                       : 1;
07737     uint64_t l2ddbe                       : 1;
07738     uint64_t tagsbe                       : 1;
07739     uint64_t tagdbe                       : 1;

07741     uint64_t vbfdbe                       : 1;

07746 #endif

07759     uint64_t rddislmc                     : 1;  /**< Illegal read to disabled LMC error. A DRAM read arrived before the LMC(s) were enabled. */
07760     uint64_t bigrd                        : 1;  /**< Read reference past L2C_BIG_CTL[MAXDRAM] occurred. */
07761     uint64_t bigwr                        : 1;  /**< Write reference past L2C_BIG_CTL[MAXDRAM] occurred. */
07762     uint64_t holerd                       : 1;  /**< Read reference to 256MB hole occurred. */
07763     uint64_t holewr                       : 1;  /**< Write reference to 256MB hole occurred. */
07764     uint64_t noway                        : 1;  /**< No way was available for allocation. L2C sets [NOWAY] during its processing of a
07765                                                          transaction
07766                                                          whenever it needed/wanted to allocate a WAY in the L2 cache, but was unable to. When this
07767                                                          bit = 1, it is (generally) not an indication that L2C failed to complete transactions.
07768                                                          Rather, it is a hint of possible performance degradation. (For example, L2C must read-
07769                                                          modify-write DRAM for every transaction that updates some, but not all, of the bytes in a
07770                                                          cache block, misses in the L2 cache, and cannot allocate a WAY.) There is one 'failure'
07771                                                          case where L2C sets [NOWAY]: when it cannot leave a block locked in the L2 cache as part
07772                                                          of
07773                                                          a LCKL2 transaction. See L2C_TTG()_ERR for logged information. */
07774     uint64_t tagdbe                       : 1;  /**< TAG double-bit error occurred. See L2C_TTG()_ERR for logged information. */
07775     uint64_t tagsbe                       : 1;  /**< TAG single-bit error occurred. See L2C_TTG()_ERR for logged information. */
07776     uint64_t reserved_6_7                 : 2;
07777     uint64_t fbfdbe                       : 1;  /**< FBF double-bit error occurred. See L2C_TQD()_ERR for logged information. */
07778     uint64_t fbfsbe                       : 1;  /**< FBF single-bit error occurred. See L2C_TQD()_ERR for logged information. */
07779     uint64_t sbfdbe                       : 1;  /**< SBF double-bit error occurred. See L2C_TQD()_ERR for logged information. */
07780     uint64_t sbfsbe                       : 1;  /**< SBF single-bit error occurred. See L2C_TQD()_ERR for logged information. */
07781     uint64_t l2ddbe                       : 1;  /**< L2D double-bit error occurred. See L2C_TQD()_ERR for logged information. */
07782     uint64_t l2dsbe                       : 1;  /**< L2D single-bit error occurred. See L2C_TQD()_ERR for logged information. */
07783 #else
07784     uint64_t l2dsbe                       : 1;
07785     uint64_t l2ddbe                       : 1;
07786     uint64_t sbfsbe                       : 1;

07812     uint64_t rtgdbe                       : 1;  /**< RTG double-bit error.
07813                                                          See L2C_TAD()_RTG_ERR for logged information.
07814                                                          An indication of a hardware failure and may be considered fatal. */
07815     uint64_t rtgsbe                       : 1;  /**< RTG single-bit error on a read. See L2C_TAD()_RTG_ERR for logged
07816                                                          information. When [RTGSBE] is set, hardware corrected the error before using the
07817                                                          RTG tag, but did not correct any stored value. When [RTGSBE] is set, software
07818                                                          should eject the RTG location indicated by the corresponding
07819                                                          L2C_TAD()_RTG_ERR[WAY,L2IDX] before clearing [RTGSBE]. Otherwise, hardware may
07820                                                          encounter the error again the next time the same RTG location is
07821                                                          referenced. Software may also choose to count the number of these single-bit
07822                                                          errors.
07823                                                          The eject should use a CACHE 0x3 instruction with an effective address of:
07824                                                          <pre>
07825                                                            payload<24> = 1
07826                                                            payload<23:20> = L2C_TAD()_RTG_ERR[WAY]
07827                                                            payload<19:7>  = L2C_TAD()_RTG_ERR[L2IDX]
07828                                                          </pre> */
07829     uint64_t reserved_18_31               : 14;
07830     uint64_t lfbto                        : 1;  /**< An LFB entry (or more) has encountered a timeout condition When LFBTO timeout condition
07831                                                          occurs L2C_TAD()_TIMEOUT is loaded. L2C_TAD()_TIMEOUT is loaded with info from the
07832                                                          first LFB that timed out. if multiple LFB timed out simultaneously, then the it will
07833                                                          capture info from the lowest LFB number that timed out.
07834                                                          Should not occur during normal operation.  OCI/CCPI link failures may cause this
07835                                                          failure. This may be an indication of hardware failure, and may be considered
07836                                                          fatal. */
07837     uint64_t wrdislmc                     : 1;  /**< Illegal write to disabled LMC error. A DRAM write arrived before LMC was enabled.
07838                                                          Should not occur during normal operation.
07839                                                          This may be considered fatal. */
07840     uint64_t rddislmc                     : 1;  /**< Illegal read to disabled LMC error. A DRAM read arrived before LMC was enabled.
07841                                                          Should not occur during normal operation.
07842                                                          This may be considered fatal. */
07843     uint64_t bigrd                        : 1;  /**< Read reference past L2C_BIG_CTL[MAXDRAM] occurred. [BIGRD] interrupts can occur during
07844                                                          normal operation as the cores are allowed to prefetch to nonexistent memory locations.
07845                                                          Therefore, [BIGRD] is for informational purposes only. See L2C_TAD()_ERR for logged
07846                                                          information. */
07847     uint64_t bigwr                        : 1;  /**< Write reference past L2C_BIG_CTL[MAXDRAM] occurred. See L2C_TAD()_ERR for logged information. */
07848     uint64_t reserved_11_12               : 2;
07849     uint64_t noway                        : 1;  /**< No way was available for allocation. L2C sets [NOWAY] during its processing of a
07850                                                          transaction
07851                                                          whenever it needed/wanted to allocate a WAY in the L2 cache, but was unable to. When this
07852                                                          bit = 1, it is (generally) not an indication that L2C failed to complete transactions.
07853                                                          Rather, it is a hint of possible performance degradation. (For example, L2C must read-
07854                                                          modify-write DRAM for every transaction that updates some, but not all, of the bytes in a
07855                                                          cache block, misses in the L2 cache, and cannot allocate a WAY.) There is one 'failure'
07856                                                          case where L2C sets [NOWAY]: when it cannot leave a block locked in the L2 cache as part
07857                                                          of
07858                                                          a LCKL2 transaction. See L2C_TTG()_ERR for logged information. */
07859     uint64_t tagdbe                       : 1;  /**< TAG double-bit error occurred. See L2C_TTG()_ERR for logged information.
07860                                                          This is an indication of a hardware failure and may be considered fatal. */
07861     uint64_t tagsbe                       : 1;  /**< TAG single-bit error on a read. See L2C_TAD()_TTG_ERR for logged
07862                                                          information. When [TAGSBE] is set, hardware corrected the error before using the
07863                                                          tag, but did not correct any stored value. When [TAGSBE] is set, software should
07864                                                          eject the TAG location indicated by the corresponding
07865                                                          L2C_TAD()_TTG_ERR[WAY,L2IDX] before clearing [TAGSBE]. Otherwise, hardware may
07866                                                          encounter the error again the next time the same TAG location is
07867                                                          referenced. Software may also choose to count the number of these single-bit
07868                                                          errors.
07869                                                          The eject should use a CACHE 0x3 instruction with an effective address of:
07870                                                            <pre>
07871                                                            payload<24> = 0
07872                                                            payload<23:20> = L2C_TAD()_TTG_ERR[WAY]
07873                                                            payload<19:7>  = L2C_TAD()_TTG_ERR[L2IDX]
07874                                                            </pre>
07875                                                          Note that L2C_CTL[DISIDXALIAS] has no effect on this payload. */
07876     uint64_t reserved_6_7                 : 2;
07877     uint64_t fbfdbe                       : 1;  /**< FBF double-bit error occurred. See L2C_TAD()_TQD_ERR for logged information. An
07878                                                          indication of a hardware failure and may be considered fatal. */

07880                                                          information. Hardware automatically corrected the error. Software may choose to
07881                                                          count the number of these single-bit errors. */
07882     uint64_t sbfdbe                       : 1;  /**< SBF double-bit error occurred. See L2C_TAD()_TQD_ERR for logged information. An
07883                                                          indication of a hardware failure and may be considered fatal. */
07884     uint64_t sbfsbe                       : 1;  /**< SBF single-bit error on a read. See L2C_TAD()_TQD_ERR for logged
07885                                                          information. Hardware automatically corrected the error. Software may choose to
07886                                                          count the number of these single-bit errors. */
07887     uint64_t l2ddbe                       : 1;  /**< L2D double-bit error occurred. See L2C_TAD()_TQD_ERR for logged information. An
07888                                                          indication of a hardware failure and may be considered fatal. */
07889     uint64_t l2dsbe                       : 1;  /**< L2D single-bit error on a read. See L2C_TAD()_TQD_ERR for logged
07890                                                          information. When [L2DSBE] is set, hardware corrected the error before using the
07891                                                          data, but did not correct any stored value. When [L2DSBE] is set, software
07892                                                          should eject the cache block indicated by the corresponding
07893                                                          L2C_TAD()_TQD_ERR[QDNUM,L2DIDX] before clearing [L2DSBE]. Otherwise, hardware
07894                                                          may encounter the error again the next time the same L2D location is
07895                                                          referenced. Software may also choose to count the number of these single-bit
07896                                                          errors.
07897                                                          The eject should use a CACHE 0x3 instruction with an effective address of:
07898                                                          <pre>
07899                                                            payload<24:22> = 0
07900                                                            payload<21:18> = L2C_TAD()_TQD_ERR[L2DIDX]<10:7>  // way
07901                                                            payload<17:11> = L2C_TAD()_TQD_ERR[L2DIDX]<6:0>   // index<10:4>
07902                                                            payload<10:9>  = L2C_TAD()_TQD_ERR[L2DIDX]<12:11> // index<3:2>
07903                                                            payload<8:7>   = tad             // index<1:0>
07904                                                          </pre>
07905                                                          where tad is the TAD index from this CSR. Note that L2C_CTL[DISIDXALIAS] has no
07906                                                          effect on the payload. */
07907 #else

07909     uint64_t l2ddbe                       : 1;
07910     uint64_t sbfsbe                       : 1;
07911     uint64_t sbfdbe                       : 1;
07912     uint64_t fbfsbe                       : 1;

07914     uint64_t reserved_6_7                 : 2;

07925     uint64_t rtgsbe                       : 1;
07926     uint64_t rtgdbe                       : 1;
07927     uint64_t rddisoci                     : 1;
07928     uint64_t wrdisoci                     : 1;

07930 #endif

08099 /**

08234                                                          0x1 = Shared.

08298 /**
08299  * cvmx_l2c_tad#_timeout
08300  *
08301  * This register records error information for an LFBTO (LFB TimeOut). The first LFBTO error will
08302  * lock the register until the logged error type s cleared. If multiple LFBs timed out
08303  * simultaneously, then this will contain the information form the lowest LFB number that has
08304  * timed-out. The address can be for the original transaction address or the replacement address
08305  * (if both could have timed out, then the transaction address will be here).
08306  */
08307 union cvmx_l2c_tadx_timeout {
08308     uint64_t u64;
08309     struct cvmx_l2c_tadx_timeout_s {
08310 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08311     uint64_t infolfb                      : 1;  /**< Logged address information is for the LFB original transation. */
08312     uint64_t infovab                      : 1;  /**< Logged address information is for the VAB (replacement). If both this and [INFOLFB] is
08313                                                          set,
08314                                                          then both could have timed out, but info captured is from the original LFB. */
08315     uint64_t reserved_57_61               : 5;
08316     uint64_t lfbnum                       : 5;  /**< The LFB number of the entry that timed out, and have its info captures in this register. */
08317     uint64_t cmd                          : 8;  /**< Encoding of XMC command causing error. */
08318     uint64_t node                         : 4;  /**< Home node of the address causing the error. Similar to [ADDR] below, this can be the
08319                                                          request address (if [INFOLFB] is set), else it is the replacement address (if [INFOLFB] is
08320                                                          clear & [INFOVAB] is set). */
08321     uint64_t addr                         : 33; /**< Cache line address causing the error. This can be either the request address or the
08322                                                          replacement (if [INFOLFB] is set), else it is the replacement address (if [INFOLFB] is
08323                                                          clear &
08324                                                          [INFOVAB] is set). This address is a physical address. L2C performs hole removal and index
08325                                                          aliasing (if enabled) on the written address and uses that for the command. This hole-
08326                                                          removed/index-aliased address is what is returned on a read of L2C_XMC_CMD. */
08327     uint64_t reserved_0_6                 : 7;
08328 #else
08329     uint64_t reserved_0_6                 : 7;
08330     uint64_t addr                         : 33;
08331     uint64_t node                         : 4;
08332     uint64_t cmd                          : 8;
08333     uint64_t lfbnum                       : 5;
08334     uint64_t reserved_57_61               : 5;
08335     uint64_t infovab                      : 1;
08336     uint64_t infolfb                      : 1;
08337 #endif
08338     } s;
08339     struct cvmx_l2c_tadx_timeout_s        cn73xx;
08340     struct cvmx_l2c_tadx_timeout_s        cn78xx;
08341     struct cvmx_l2c_tadx_timeout_s        cn78xxp1;
08342     struct cvmx_l2c_tadx_timeout_s        cnf75xx;
08343 };
08344 typedef union cvmx_l2c_tadx_timeout cvmx_l2c_tadx_timeout_t;

08352 union cvmx_l2c_tadx_timetwo {

08359     uint64_t vabst                        : 3;  /**< This is the LFB internal state if INFOLFB is set, else will contain VAB internal state if

08372 #endif
