08497 /**
08498  * cvmx_l2c_tqd#_err
08499  *
08500  * This register records error information for all L2D/SBF/FBF errors.
08501  * An error locks [L2DIDX] and [SYN] and sets the bit corresponding to the error received.
08502  * DBE errors take priority and overwrite an earlier logged SBE error. Only one of SBE/DBE is set
08503  * at any given time and serves to document which error the [L2DIDX]/[SYN] is associated with.
08504  * The syndrome is recorded for DBE errors, though the utility of the value is not clear.
08505  */
08506 union cvmx_l2c_tqdx_err {

08520     uint64_t qdhlf                        : 1;  /**< Quad half of the containing the error. */
08521     uint64_t l2didx                       : 14; /**< For L2D errors, index within the quad-half containing the error. For SBF and FBF errors
08522                                                          <13:5> is 0x0 and <4:0> is the index of the error (<4:1> is lfbnum<3:0>, <0> is addr<5>). */
08523 #else
08524     uint64_t l2didx                       : 14;
08525     uint64_t qdhlf                        : 1;
08526     uint64_t qdnum                        : 3;
08527     uint64_t reserved_18_31               : 14;
08528     uint64_t syn                          : 8;
08529     uint64_t reserved_40_57               : 18;
08530     uint64_t fbfsbe                       : 1;
08531     uint64_t sbfsbe                       : 1;
08532     uint64_t l2dsbe                       : 1;
08533     uint64_t fbfdbe                       : 1;
08534     uint64_t sbfdbe                       : 1;
08535     uint64_t l2ddbe                       : 1;
08536 #endif
08537     } s;
08538     struct cvmx_l2c_tqdx_err_s            cn70xx;
08539     struct cvmx_l2c_tqdx_err_s            cn70xxp1;

08596 /**
08597  * cvmx_l2c_ttg#_err
08598  *
08599  * This register records error information for all TAG SBE/DBE/NOWAY errors.
08600  * The priority of errors (lowest to highest) is NOWAY, SBE, DBE. An error locks [SYN], [WAY],
08601  * and [L2IDX] for equal or lower priority errors until cleared by software.
08602  * The syndrome is recorded for DBE errors, though the utility of the value is not clear.
08603  * A NOWAY error does not change the value of [SYN] field, and leaves [WAY] unpredictable.
08604  * L2IDX<17:7> is the L2 block index associated with the command which had no way to allocate.
08605  */
08606 union cvmx_l2c_ttgx_err {
08607     uint64_t u64;
08608     struct cvmx_l2c_ttgx_err_s {
08609 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08610     uint64_t tagdbe                       : 1;  /**< Information refers to a double-bit TAG ECC error. */
08611     uint64_t tagsbe                       : 1;  /**< Information refers to a single-bit TAG ECC error. */
08612     uint64_t noway                        : 1;  /**< Information refers to a NOWAY error. */
08613     uint64_t reserved_39_60               : 22;
08614     uint64_t syn                          : 7;  /**< Syndrome for the single-bit error. */
08615     uint64_t reserved_0_31                : 32;
08616 #else
08617     uint64_t reserved_0_31                : 32;
08618     uint64_t syn                          : 7;
08619     uint64_t reserved_39_60               : 22;
08620     uint64_t noway                        : 1;
08621     uint64_t tagsbe                       : 1;
08622     uint64_t tagdbe                       : 1;
08623 #endif
08624     } s;
08625     struct cvmx_l2c_ttgx_err_cn70xx {
08626 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08627     uint64_t tagdbe                       : 1;  /**< Information refers to a double-bit TAG ECC error. */
08628     uint64_t tagsbe                       : 1;  /**< Information refers to a single-bit TAG ECC error. */
08629     uint64_t noway                        : 1;  /**< Information refers to a NOWAY error. */
08630     uint64_t reserved_39_60               : 22;
08631     uint64_t syn                          : 7;  /**< Syndrome for the single-bit error. */
08632     uint64_t reserved_19_31               : 13;
08633     uint64_t way                          : 2;  /**< Way of the L2 block containing the error */
08634     uint64_t l2idx                        : 10; /**< Index of the L2 block containing the error */
08635     uint64_t reserved_0_6                 : 7;
08636 #else
08637     uint64_t reserved_0_6                 : 7;
08638     uint64_t l2idx                        : 10;
08639     uint64_t way                          : 2;
08640     uint64_t reserved_19_31               : 13;
08641     uint64_t syn                          : 7;
08642     uint64_t reserved_39_60               : 22;
08643     uint64_t noway                        : 1;
08644     uint64_t tagsbe                       : 1;
08645     uint64_t tagdbe                       : 1;
08646 #endif
08647     } cn70xx;

08651     uint64_t tagdbe                       : 1;  /**< Information refers to a double-bit TAG ECC error. */
08652     uint64_t tagsbe                       : 1;  /**< Information refers to a single-bit TAG ECC error. */
08653     uint64_t noway                        : 1;  /**< Information refers to a NOWAY error. */
08654     uint64_t reserved_39_60               : 22;
08655     uint64_t syn                          : 7;  /**< Syndrome for the single-bit error. */
08656     uint64_t reserved_22_31               : 10;
08657     uint64_t way                          : 4;  /**< Way of the L2 block containing the error. */
08658     uint64_t l2idx                        : 11; /**< Index of the L2 block containing the error.
08659                                                          See L2C_TAD()_INT[TAGSBE] for an important use of this field. */

08666     uint64_t syn                          : 7;
08667     uint64_t reserved_39_60               : 22;
08668     uint64_t noway                        : 1;
08669     uint64_t tagsbe                       : 1;
08670     uint64_t tagdbe                       : 1;
08671 #endif
08672     } cn73xx;
08673     struct cvmx_l2c_ttgx_err_cn78xx {
08674 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08675     uint64_t tagdbe                       : 1;  /**< Information refers to a double-bit TAG ECC error. */

08905 /**
08906  * cvmx_l2c_vrt_ctl
08907  *
08908  * L2C_VRT_CTL = L2C Virtualization control register
08909  *
08910  */
08911 union cvmx_l2c_vrt_ctl {
08912     uint64_t u64;
08913     struct cvmx_l2c_vrt_ctl_s {
08914 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
08915     uint64_t reserved_9_63                : 55;
08916     uint64_t ooberr                       : 1;  /**< Whether out of bounds writes are an error
08917                                                          Determines virtualization hardware behavior for
08918                                                          a store to an L2/DRAM address larger than
08919                                                          indicated by MEMSZ. If OOBERR is set, all these
08920                                                          stores (from any virtualization ID) are blocked. If
08921                                                          OOBERR is clear, none of these stores are blocked. */
08922     uint64_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
08923     uint64_t memsz                        : 3;  /**< Memory space coverage of L2C_VRT_MEM (encoded)
08924                                                          0 = 1GB
08925                                                          1 = 2GB
08926                                                          2 = 4GB
08927                                                          3 = 8GB
08928                                                          4 = 16GB
08929                                                          5 = 32GB
08930                                                          6 = 64GB (**reserved in 63xx**)
08931                                                          7 = 128GB (**reserved in 63xx**) */
08932     uint64_t numid                        : 3;  /**< Number of allowed virtualization IDs (encoded)
08933                                                              0 = 2
08934                                                              1 = 4
08935                                                              2 = 8
08936                                                              3 = 16
08937                                                              4 = 32
08938                                                              5 = 64
08939                                                              6,7 illegal
08940                                                          Violations of this limit causes
08941                                                          L2C to set L2C_INT_REG[VRTIDRNG]. */
08942     uint64_t enable                       : 1;  /**< Global virtualization enable
08943                                                          When ENABLE is clear, stores are never blocked by
08944                                                          the L2C virtualization hardware and none of NUMID,
08945                                                          MEMSZ, OOBERR are used. */
08946 #else
08947     uint64_t enable                       : 1;
08948     uint64_t numid                        : 3;
08949     uint64_t memsz                        : 3;
08950     uint64_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
08951     uint64_t ooberr                       : 1;
08952     uint64_t reserved_9_63                : 55;
08953 #endif
08954     } s;

08956     struct cvmx_l2c_vrt_ctl_s             cn63xx;

08965 /**
08966  * cvmx_l2c_vrt_mem#
08967  *
08968  * L2C_VRT_MEM = L2C Virtualization Memory
08969  *
08970  * Description: Virtualization memory mapped region.  There are 1024 32b
08971  * byte-parity protected entries.
08972  *
08973  * Notes:
08974  * When a DATA bit is set in L2C_VRT_MEM when L2C virtualization is enabled, L2C
08975  * prevents the selected virtual machine from storing to the selected L2/DRAM region.
08976  * L2C uses L2C_VRT_MEM to block stores when:
08977  *  - L2C_VRT_CTL[ENABLE] is set, and
08978  *  - the address of the store exists in L2C+LMC internal L2/DRAM Address space
08979  *    and is within the L2C_VRT_CTL[MEMSZ] bounds, and
08980  *  - the virtID of the store is within the L2C_VRT_CTL[NUMID] bounds
08981  *
08982  * L2C_VRT_MEM is never used for these L2C transactions which are always allowed:
08983  *   - L2C CMI L2/DRAM transactions that cannot modify L2/DRAM, and
08984  *   - any L2/DRAM transaction originated from L2C_XMC_CMD
08985  *
08986  * L2C_VRT_MEM contains one DATA bit per L2C+LMC internal L2/DRAM region and virtID indicating whether the store
08987  * to the region is allowed. The granularity of the checking is the region size, which is:
08988  *       2 ^^ (L2C_VRT_CTL[NUMID]+L2C_VRT_CTL[MEMSZ]+16)
08989  * which ranges from a minimum of 64KB to a maximum of 256MB, depending on the size
08990  * of L2/DRAM that is protected and the number of virtual machines.
08991  *
08992  * The L2C_VRT_MEM DATA bit that L2C uses is:
08993  *
08994  *   l2c_vrt_mem_bit_index = address >> (L2C_VRT_CTL[MEMSZ]+L2C_VRT_CTL[NUMID]+16); // address is a byte address
08995  *   l2c_vrt_mem_bit_index = l2c_vrt_mem_bit_index | (virtID << (14-L2C_VRT_CTL[NUMID]));
08996  *
08997  *   L2C_VRT_MEM(l2c_vrt_mem_bit_index >> 5)[DATA<l2c_vrt_mem_bit_index & 0x1F>] is used
08998  *
08999  * A specific example:
09000  *
09001  *   L2C_VRT_CTL[NUMID]=2 (i.e. 8 virtual machine ID's used)
09002  *   L2C_VRT_CTL[MEMSZ]=4 (i.e. L2C_VRT_MEM covers 16 GB)
09003  *
09004  *   L2/DRAM region size (granularity) is 4MB
09005  *
09006  *   l2c_vrt_mem_bit_index<14:12> = virtID<2:0>
09007  *   l2c_vrt_mem_bit_index<11:0> = address<33:22>
09008  *
09009  *   For L2/DRAM physical address 0x51000000 with virtID=5:
09010  *      L2C_VRT_MEM648[DATA<4>] determines when the store is allowed (648 is decimal, not hex)
09011  */
09012 union cvmx_l2c_vrt_memx {
09013     uint64_t u64;
09014     struct cvmx_l2c_vrt_memx_s {
09015 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
09016     uint64_t reserved_36_63               : 28;
09017     uint64_t parity                       : 4;  /**< Parity to write into (or read from) the
09018                                                          virtualization memory.
09019                                                          PARITY<i> is the even parity of DATA<(i*8)+7:i*8> */
09020     uint64_t data                         : 32; /**< Data to write into (or read from) the
09021                                                          virtualization memory. */
09022 #else
09023     uint64_t data                         : 32;
09024     uint64_t parity                       : 4;
09025     uint64_t reserved_36_63               : 28;
09026 #endif
09027     } s;
09028     struct cvmx_l2c_vrt_memx_s            cn61xx;
09029     struct cvmx_l2c_vrt_memx_s            cn63xx;
09030     struct cvmx_l2c_vrt_memx_s            cn63xxp1;
09031     struct cvmx_l2c_vrt_memx_s            cn66xx;
09032     struct cvmx_l2c_vrt_memx_s            cn68xx;
09033     struct cvmx_l2c_vrt_memx_s            cn68xxp1;
09034     struct cvmx_l2c_vrt_memx_s            cnf71xx;
09035 };
09036 typedef union cvmx_l2c_vrt_memx cvmx_l2c_vrt_memx_t;

09163 /**
09164  * cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd
09165  *
09166  * Note the following:
09167  * The ADD bus command chosen must not be a IOB-destined command or operation is UNDEFINED.
09168  *
09169  * The ADD bus command will have SID forced to IOB, DID forced to L2C, no virtualization checks
09170  * performed (always pass), and xmdmsk forced to 0. Note that this implies that commands that
09171  * REQUIRE a STORE cycle (STP, STC, SAA, FAA, FAS) should not be used or the results are
09172  * unpredictable. The sid = IOB means that the way partitioning used for the command is
09173  * L2C_WPAR_IOB(). Neither L2C_QOS_IOB() nor L2C_QOS_PP() are used for these
09174  * commands.
09175  *
09176  * Any FILL responses generated by the ADD bus command are ignored. Generated STINs, however,
09177  * will correctly invalidate the required cores.
09178  *
09179  * A write that arrives while [INUSE] is set will block until [INUSE] clears. This
09180  * gives software two options when needing to issue a stream of write operations to L2C_XMC_CMD:
09181  * polling on [INUSE], or allowing hardware to handle the interlock -- at the expense of
09182  * locking up the RSL bus for potentially tens of cycles at a time while waiting for an available
09183  * LFB/VAB entry. Note that when [INUSE] clears, the only ordering it implies is that
09184  * software can send another ADD bus command. Subsequent commands may complete out of order
09185  * relative to earlier commands.
09186  *
09187  * The address written to L2C_XMC_CMD is a physical address. L2C performs hole removal and index
09188  * aliasing (if enabled) on the written address and uses that for the command. This hole
09189  * removed/index aliased address is what is returned on a read of the L2C_XMC_CMD register.
09190  */
09191 union cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd {
09192     uint64_t u64;
09193     struct cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd_s {
09194 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
09195     uint64_t inuse                        : 1;  /**< Set to 1 by hardware upon receiving a write; cleared when command has issued (not
09196                                                          necessarily completed, but ordered relative to other traffic) and hardware can accept
09197                                                          another command. */
09198     uint64_t reserved_47_62               : 16;
09199     uint64_t qos                          : 3;  /**< QOS level to use for simulated ADD bus request. */
09200     uint64_t node                         : 4;  /**< Ignored because CCPI is not present. Will return the value written, but the
09201                                                          simulated ADD bus request will use a node of 0. */
09202     uint64_t addr                         : 40; /**< Address to use for simulated ADD bus request. (The address written to L2C_XMC_CMD is a
09203                                                          physical address. L2C performs hole removal and index aliasing (if enabled) on the written
09204                                                          address and uses that for the command. This hole-removed/index-aliased address is what is
09205                                                          returned on a read of L2C_XMC_CMD.) */
09206 #else
09207     uint64_t addr                         : 40;
09208     uint64_t node                         : 4;
09209     uint64_t qos                          : 3;
09210     uint64_t reserved_47_62               : 16;
09211     uint64_t inuse                        : 1;
09212 #endif
09213     } s;
09214     struct cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd_cn61xx {
09215 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
09216     uint64_t inuse                        : 1;  /**< Set to 1 by HW upon receiving a write, cleared when
09217                                                          command has issued (not necessarily completed, but
09218                                                          ordered relative to other traffic) and HW can accept
09219                                                          another command. */
09220     uint64_t cmd                          : 6;  /**< Command to use for simulated XMC request
09221                                                          a new request can be accepted */
09222     uint64_t reserved_38_56               : 19;
09223     uint64_t addr                         : 38; /**< Address to use for simulated XMC request (see Note 6) */
09224 #else
09225     uint64_t addr                         : 38;
09226     uint64_t reserved_38_56               : 19;
09227     uint64_t cmd                          : 6;
09228     uint64_t inuse                        : 1;
09229 #endif
09230     } cn61xx;
09231     struct cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd_cn61xx        cn63xx;
09232     struct cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd_cn61xx        cn63xxp1;
09233     struct cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd_cn61xx        cn66xx;
09234     struct cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd_cn61xx        cn68xx;
09235     struct cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd_cn61xx        cn68xxp1;
09236     struct cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd_cn70xx {
09237 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
09238     uint64_t inuse                        : 1;  /**< Set to 1 by hardware upon receiving a write; cleared when command has issued (not
09239                                                          necessarily completed, but ordered relative to other traffic) and hardware can accept
09240                                                          another command. */
09241     uint64_t cmd                          : 7;  /**< Command to use for simulated ADD bus request. A new request can be accepted. */
09242     uint64_t reserved_47_55               : 9;
09243     uint64_t qos                          : 3;  /**< QOS level to use for simulated ADD bus request. */
09244     uint64_t node                         : 4;  /**< Must be zero. */
09245     uint64_t addr                         : 40; /**< Address to use for simulated ADD bus request. (The address written to L2C_XMC_CMD is a
09246                                                          physical address. L2C performs hole removal and index aliasing (if enabled) on the written
09247                                                          address and uses that for the command. This hole-removed/index-aliased address is what is
09248                                                          returned on a read of L2C_XMC_CMD.) */
09249 #else
09250     uint64_t addr                         : 40;
09251     uint64_t node                         : 4;
09252     uint64_t qos                          : 3;
09253     uint64_t reserved_47_55               : 9;
09254     uint64_t cmd                          : 7;
09255     uint64_t inuse                        : 1;
09256 #endif
09257     } cn70xx;
09258     struct cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd_cn70xx        cn70xxp1;
09259     struct cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd_cn70xx        cn73xx;
09260     struct cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd_cn70xx        cn78xx;
09261     struct cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd_cn70xx        cn78xxp1;
09262     struct cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd_cn61xx        cnf71xx;
09263     struct cvmx_l2c_xmc_cmd_cn70xx        cnf75xx;
